ss=\"wikitable sortable\" \n|-\n! Year \n! Title \n! Role \n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes \n|- \n| 2002 \n| ''[[Stranded (2002 film)|Stranded]]'' \n| Young Sarah Robinson \n| Television film \n|- \n| 2004 \n| ''[[Agatha Christie: A Life in Pictures]]''  \n| Young [[Agatha Christie]] \n| Television film \n|- \n| 2007 \n| ''[[The Replacements (TV series)|The Replacements]]''  \n| Vanessa \n| Episode: \"London Calling\"; voice role \n|} \n\n===Theatre===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[The Moment of Truth (play)|The Moment of Truth]]''\n| The Girl\n| [[Southwark Playhouse]]\n|}\n\n===Video games===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Game\n! Voice role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix (video game)|Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix]]''\n| rowspan=\"4\" | Ginny Weasley\n|\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince (video game)|Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince]]''\n|\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows \u2013 Part 1 (video game)|Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows \u2013 Part 1]]''\n|\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows - Part 2 (video game)|Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows - Part 2]]''\n|\n|}\n\n===Theme parks===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Voice role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2010\n| [[Harry Potter and the Forbidden Journey]]\n| Ginny Weasley\n| Theme park attraction. [[The Wizarding World of Harry Potter]]\n|}\n\n===Director===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Film\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[Separate We Come, Separate We Go]]''\n| Director only, directorial debut\n| Premiered at the Cannes Film Festival short film corner\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''Dreaming''\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Director\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Music video\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | 2014\n| ''Sea Ess''\n|-\n| ''Know Thyself''\n| Writer, director and producer\n| Short film, premiered at the New Film Makers New York at Anthology Film Archive in 2016\n|-\n| ''Fade to Gold''\n| rowspan=\"5\" | Director\n| Short film for ''LoveGold and Wright and Teague''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | 2018\n| ''Medusa's Ankles''\n| Short film based on ''Medusa's Ankles'' by author A. S. Byatt\n|-\n| ''Taught You How To Feel''\n| rowspan=\"3\" | Music video\n|-\n| ''Iguana Bird''\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''Fallible''\n|}\n\n===Screenwriter===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Film\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[Separate We Come, Separate We Go]]''\n| Screenwriter only, screenwriting debut\n| Premiered at the Cannes Film Festival short film corner\n|}\n\n===Other roles===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2020\n|''Babbitty Rabbitty and her Cackling Stump''\n| Narrator\n| Audiobook of [[The Tales of Beedle the Bard]].<ref>[https://www.wizardingworld.com/news/beedle-the-bard-audiobook-announcement New audiobook The Tales of Beedle the Bard is coming soon] Wizardingworld.com. Retrieved on 26 February 2020.</ref>  \n|}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ Awards\n|-\n! Year\n! Award\n! Category\n! Film\n! Result\n|-\n|2011\n|Rodial Beautiful Awards<ref name=\"Rodial.co.uk\"/>\n|Most Edgy Look Award\n| ''[[Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows]]''\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|2012\n|[[Empire Award]]<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://www.empireonline.com/movies/news/jameson-empire-award-nominations-2012/ |title=The Awards Nominations Are Here! |first=Helen |last=O'Hara |journal=[[Empire Online]] |date=5 March 2012 |access-date=5 March 2012}}</ref>\n| Best Female Newcomer\n| ''[[Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows&nbsp;\u2013 Part 2]]''\n|{{nom}}\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Harry Potter films cast members]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Bonnie Wright}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*{{IMDb name|0942247}}\n*{{Twitter}}\n*{{cite news|url=https://www.ew.com/ew/gallery/0,,20290,736,00.html|title='Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince': 8 EW Exclusive Cast Pics |publisher=Entertainment Weekly |date=10 July 2009 |first=Jeff |last=Jenson |accessdate=13 June 2010}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.instyle.co.uk/news/instyle-celebrates-new-british-talent-27-01-10|title=InStyle celebrates new British talent |publisher=InStyle.co.uk |date=27 January 2010 |first=Pat |last=McNulty |accessdate=13 June 2010}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wright, Bonnie}}\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Actresses from London]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of the Arts London]]\n[[Category:English child actresses]]\n[[Category:English film actresses]]\n[[Category:English television actresses]]\n[[Category:English voice actresses]]\n[[Category:People educated at King Alfred School, London]]\n[[Category:21st-century English actresses]]\n[[Category:English female models]]\n[[Category:English music video directors]]\n[[Category:English film directors]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|English actress, model, screenwriter, director and producer}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Bonnie Wright\n| image = Bonnie Wright by Gage Skidmore 2.jpg\n| caption = Wright at the 2017 [[Phoenix Comicon]]\n| birth_name = Bonnie Francesca Wright\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1991|2|17}}\n| birth_place = [[London Borough of Tower Hamlets|Tower Hamlets]], [[London]], England\n| occupation = {{hlist|Actress|Director|Producer|Screenwriter|Model|Activist}}\n| alma_mater = [[London College of Communication]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]])\n| years_active = 2001\u2013present\n|known_for = {{plainlist|\n* [[Ginny Weasley]] in ''[[Harry Potter (film series)|Harry Potter]]''}}\n}}\n\n'''Bonnie Francesca Wright'''<ref name=birth>''Births, Marriages & Deaths Index of England & Wales, 1916\u20132005.''; at ancestry.com</ref> (born 17 February 1991)<ref name=ond>{{cite book|last=Merrill|first=Brian|authorlink=|title=On This Date: A Day-by-Day Look at Historical Events|publisher=Lulu.com|year=2006|location=|page=36|url=|isbn=978-1-4303-0501-9}}{{self-published source}}</ref>{{self-published inline|date=February 2020}} is an English actress, film director, screenwriter, model, producer, and activist. She is best known for playing the role of [[Ginny Weasley]] in the [[Harry Potter (film series)|''Harry Potter'' film series]] based on the [[Harry Potter|novel series of the same name]] by [[J. K. Rowling]].\n\n==Early life==\nBonnie Wright was born in London, the second child of Sheila Teague and Gary Wright, owners of the jewellery company Wright & Teague. Wright attended Prior Weston Primary School and later the [[King Alfred School, London|King Alfred School]] in [[North London]] for her secondary education.<ref>{{cite news|last=Slater|first=Lydia|title=The magic of Bonnie Wright|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/the-magic-of-bonnie-wright-6784867.html|accessdate=17 June 2013|newspaper=[[Evening Standard]]|date=25 June 2009}}</ref>\n\nDuring the filming of ''[[Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows&nbsp;\u2013 Part 1]]'' and ''[[Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows&nbsp;\u2013 Part 2|Part 2]]'', she began attending London's [[University of the Arts London|University of the Arts]]: [[London College of Communication]], to begin studies as a [[Film and Television Production Manager]], because of her plans to continue acting and to work behind-the-scenes after filming ''[[Harry Potter (film series)|Harry Potter]]''.<ref name=\"Slater\"/><ref>{{cite book|last=Riggs|first=Thomas|title=Contemporary Theatre, Film & Television: A Biographical Guide|publisher=[[Gale Group]]|year=2007|page=341|isbn=978-0-7876-9050-2}}</ref> In 2012, she graduated with a Bachelor of Arts degree.<ref>[https://www.huffingtonpost.com/bonnie-wright Bonnie Wright profile], ''[[The Huffington Post]]''; retrieved 6 September 2014.</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Acting ===\n====2001\u20132011: ''Harry Potter'' series====\n[[File:Bonnie Wright crop2.jpg|right|thumb|Wright in 2010 at the Wizarding World of Harry Potter]]\nWright appears in the first film, ''[[Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone (film)|Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone]]'', only in a small scene set at [[London King's Cross railway station]], where her character and her mother [[Molly Weasley|Molly]] meet [[Harry Potter (character)|Harry Potter]] as four of her older brothers board the [[Hogwarts]] express. Her role became much more prominent in the second film, ''[[Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets (film)|Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets]]'', in which her character begins studies at [[Hogwarts]] and encounters a secret [[diary]] that begins to control her actions.<ref name=\"Slater\">{{cite web|author=Lydia Slater|title=The magic of Bonnie Wright|url=http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/lifestyle/article-23712043-the-magic-of-bonnie-wright.do|publisher=London Evening Standard|date=26 June 2009|accessdate=14 July 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100629130043/http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/lifestyle/article-23712043-the-magic-of-bonnie-wright.do|archivedate=29 June 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nWright had limited screen time in the third film, ''[[Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban (film)|Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban]]'' but had a large supporting role in the fourth film, ''[[Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire (film)|Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire]]''.\n\nIn ''[[Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix (film)|Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix]]'' Wright played a central role, joining [[Dumbledore's Army]] and eventually participating in the climactic scene in which the DA and the [[Order of the Phoenix (fiction)|Order of the Phoenix]] battle [[Lord Voldemort]] and his [[Death Eaters]]. Wright's central role continued in ''[[Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince (film)|Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince]]'' where she became an important [[Seeker (Quidditch)|chaser]] for the Gryffindor [[Quidditch]] team and, ultimately Harry Potter's true love interest.\n\nIn ''[[Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows]]'' Parts [[Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows \u2013 Part 1|1]] and [[Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows \u2013 Part 2|2]], Wright again reprised her central role for the last time. In these films she was seen most particularly in scenes before the three protagonists went in search of Horcruxes, the final Battle of Hogwarts and in the Epilogue set nineteen years later.\n\nWright has also provided the voice of Ginny in the video game versions of ''[[Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix (video game)|Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix]]''; ''[[Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince (video game)|Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince]]'' and ''[[Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows \u2013 Part 1 (video game)|Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows \u2013 Part 1]]''. Wright is one of the thirteen actors who has appeared in all eight films of the Harry Potter franchise. All the ''Harry Potter'' films were critical and high commercial successes. All the films as of 2014 have found places in [[List of highest-grossing films]].\n\nWright received several positive reviews for her portrayal of Ginny Weasley. ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' wrote: \"Bonnie Wright's Ginny intrigues as the sort of initial plain Jane who keeps growing on you.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.variety.com/review/VE1117940610/ |title=Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince |first=Todd |last=McCarthy |publisher=Variety |date=5 July 2009 |accessdate=13 June 2010}}</ref> Comingsoon.net wrote \"that If someone told me eight years ago that Bonnie Wright, introduced as Ginny Weasley in the first movie, would turn into such a strong dramatic actress who could carry scenes as well as the three leads, I wouldn't have believed it,\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.comingsoon.net/news/reviewsnews.php?id=56914/ |title=Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince Movie Review |first=Edward |last=Douglas |publisher=Coming Soon.net |date= 7 July 2009 |accessdate= 6 September 2012}}</ref> and [[Film School Rejects]] who also wrote \"Ginny (Bonnie Wright) in particular shines through, building on the power she gained in the last film to become an independent young woman that proves more complex with every scene.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.filmschoolrejects.com/reviews/review-harry-potter-and-the-half-blood-prince.php |title=Review: Harry Potter and The Half Blood Prince |first=Cole |last=Abaius |publisher=Film School Rejects |date=9 July 2009 |accessdate=6 September 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121023145422/http://www.filmschoolrejects.com/reviews/review-harry-potter-and-the-half-blood-prince.php |archivedate=23 October 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> While critic Taran Adarsh said, \"[Bonnie] Wright makes her impact feel nicely and beautifully as Ginny Weasley throughout the Harry Potter Series.\"\n\n''Harry Potter'' author [[J. K. Rowling]] gave a speech during the world premiere of the eighth and final film ''[[Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows \u2013 Part 2]]'' on 7 July 2011 in London, England. She announced that there are seven Harry Potter film series cast members to whom she refers as \"The Big Seven\". She named Wright as one of the seven members, along with [[Daniel Radcliffe]], [[Rupert Grint]], [[Emma Watson]], [[Tom Felton]], [[Matthew Lewis (actor)|Matthew Lewis]] and [[Evanna Lynch]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7QnyKZe6VBA |title=J.K. Rowling's Emotional Speech at the Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows Part 2 |publisher=Youtube.com |date=7 July 2011 |accessdate=7 November 2013}}</ref>\n\n====2012\u2013present: subsequent acting work====\nWright co-starred in two TV movies that were ''[[Stranded (TV film)|Stranded]]'' (2002) as the younger version of Sarah Robinson and ''[[Agatha Christie: A Life in Pictures]]'' (2004), where she played the younger version of writer [[Agatha Christie]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://unitedagents.co.uk/bonnie-wright#profile-1|title=Client Details |publisher=Unitedagents.co.uk/ |date= |accessdate=8 August 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, she guest starred on the [[Disney Channel]]'s ''[[The Replacements (TV series)|The Replacements]]'', where she voiced Vanessa in the second-season premiere titled \"London Calling\".{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}\n\nIn 2013, she co-starred in ''[[Before I Sleep (film)|Before I Sleep]]'' opposite [[David Warner (actor)|David Warner]], [[Tom Sizemore]], [[Cynthia Gibb]], [[Eric Roberts]], [[Eugene Simon]], [[Campbell Scott]] and [[Chevy Chase]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Singh|first=Anita|title=Cannes 2012: Harry Potter's Ginny Weasley directs budget film|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/cannes-film-festival/9279861/Cannes-2012-Harry-Potters-Ginny-Weasley-directs-budget-film.html|accessdate=21 May 2012| newspaper=The Telegraph|date=21 May 2012}}</ref> The film premiered at the 2013 [[Heartland Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Heartland Film Festival Tickets & Guide|url=http://prod1.agileticketing.net/websales/pages/info.aspx?evtinfo=62591~32c3ac16-2c16-4cb4-a802-4ea58728c0fe&epguid=4726aa5a-d365-491f-abd7-45d68838f3e6&|accessdate=27 September 2013}}</ref> Afterwards, she co-starred in ''[[The Sea (2013 film)|The Sea]]'', based on a John Bansville novel, as Rose the young nursemaid.<ref>{{cite web|title=United Agents \u2013 Bonnie Wright|url=http://unitedagents.co.uk/bonnie-wright#profile-1|publisher=United Agents}}</ref> The film premiered in competition at [[Edinburgh International Film Festival]] on 23 June 2013,<ref name=\"a\">{{cite web|title=Michael Powell Award Competition / World premiere|url=http://www.edfilmfest.org.uk/films/2013/the-sea|accessdate=27 June 2013}}</ref> and had its North American premiere at the [[2013 Toronto International Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Fleming Jr.|first=Mike|title=Toronto Sets World Cinema Film Lineup|url=https://www.deadline.com/2013/08/toronto-sets-world-cinema-film-lineup/|publisher=Deadline|accessdate=13 August 2013|date=2013-08-13}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, she also made her stage debut in the role of ''The Girl'' in [[Peter Ustinov]]'s ''[[The Moment of Truth (play)|The Moment of Truth]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://southwarkplayhouse.co.uk/the-large/the-moment-of-truth|title=The Moment of Truth|publisher=Southwarkplayhouse.co.uk|date=20 July 2013|accessdate=7 November 2013}}</ref> The play was performed at the [[Southwark Playhouse]] in London on 26 June 2013 prior to an official opening on 28 June 2013 for a four-week run through 20 July 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/178288-Harry-Potter-Star-Bonnie-Wright-to-Make-Stage-Debut-in-The-Moment-of-Truth-at-Londons-Southwark-Playhouse|title=\"Harry Potter\" Star Bonnie Wright to Make Stage Debut in The Moment of Truth at Southwark Playhouse|work=Playbill|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130605035818/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/178288-Harry-Potter-Star-Bonnie-Wright-to-Make-Stage-Debut-in-The-Moment-of-Truth-at-Londons-Southwark-Playhouse|archivedate=5 June 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://southwarkplayhouse.co.uk/the-large/the-moment-of-truth/ |title=The Moment of Truth, Southwark Playhouse, Retrieved 23 May 2013 |publisher=Southwarkplayhouse.co.uk |date=20 July 2013 |accessdate=7 November 2013}}</ref> Wright received positive reviews for her stage debut performance in The Moment of Truth play; the ''[[British Theatre Guide]]'' wrote \"Bonnie Wright makes clear in her performance, she is motivated by love for her father and movingly has to face rejection from her gas-masked lover when he returns as liberator\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britishtheatreguide.info/reviews/moment-of-truth-southwark-playh-8979|title=British Theatre Guide, The Moment of Truth |publisher=Britishtheatreguide.info|accessdate=7 November 2013}}</ref> ''[[The Stage (magazine)|The Stage]]'' reviewer opined that \"Bonnie Wright, in her stage debut, is perfectly acceptable as the Girl\".<ref>{{cite web|author=Paul Vale|url=http://www.thestage.co.uk/reviews/review.php/38706/the-moment-of-truth|title=The Moment of Truth|publisher=Thestage.co.uk|date=1 July 2013|accessdate=7 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Roger Smith|url=http://onestoparts.com/22/296/view/2538|title=Onestoparts.com, Whatever happened to Marshal P\u00e9tain? The Moment of Truth at Southwark Playhouse|publisher=Onestoparts.com|date=1 July 2013|accessdate=7 November 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131208165435/http://onestoparts.com/22/296/view/2538|archive-date=8 December 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, she took part in [[The Great British Bake Off#Series 3 (Sport Relief 2014)|the third series of ''The Great Sport Relief Bake Off'']], winning the first episode and being named the \"Star Baker\".<ref name=\"bbc-b03qk2kz\">{{BBC episode|id=b03qk2kz|title=The Great Sport Relief Bake Off|description=Episode 1}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Wright co-starred opposite [[Rhys Wakefield]], [[James D'Arcy]] and her ''Harry Potter'' co-star [[Freddie Stroma]] in the American [[Science fiction|Sci-fi]] film ''[[After the Dark]]'' (formerly known as ''The Philosophers''<ref name=\"b\">{{cite web|url=http://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwmovies/article/Poster-Art-Revealed-for-AFTER-THE-DARK-In-Theaters-This-February-20131216|title=Poster Art Revealed for AFTER THE DARK, In Theaters This February|publisher=broadwayworld.com|accessdate=17 December 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131217221411/http://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwmovies/article/Poster-Art-Revealed-for-AFTER-THE-DARK-In-Theaters-This-February-20131216|archive-date=17 December 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>), directed by John Huddles<ref name=\"Ross\">{{cite web|author=Ashley Ross|title=Exclusive Interview: Bonnie Wright on the End of Harry Potter|url=http://www.marieclaire.com/world-reports/opinion/bonnie-wright-harry-potter-interview|work=marieclaire.com|accessdate=21 April 2011|date=2011-04-21}}</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110617120028/http://www.thejakartaglobe.com/home/harry-potter-star-to-shoot-hollywood-movie-in-jakarta/446915 \"Harry Potter Star to Shoot Hollywood Movie in Jakarta\"], ''Jakarta Globe'', 14 June 2011.</ref> and began filming July 2011 in [[Jakarta]], Indonesia. Wright played Georgina, one of the students.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/465135/The-Philosophers/overview|title=The Philosophers|work=NYTimes.com|accessdate=21 April 2011}}</ref> The film premiered at [[Neuch\u00e2tel International Fantastic Film Festival]] on 7 July 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=THE PHILOSOPHERS/MOVIES OF THE THIRD KIND|url=http://www.nifff.ch/?a=&cat=thirdkind&movid=The_Philosophers_1370346163|accessdate=27 June 2013}}</ref> The film was released on 7 February 2014.<ref name=\"b\"/>\n\nIn late 2014, she appeared in the short film ''How (Not) to Rob a Train'' as a bandit,<ref>{{cite web|title=How (Not) to Rob a Train|url=http://annamaguire.co.uk/how-not-to-rob-a-train/|website=annamaguire.co.uk|accessdate=30 October 2014}}</ref> and as the character Mia in the short film ''Sweat'' which is one of five film segments for the feature length anthology film ''Geography of the Heart'' about \"the complexity of intimacy, shot in five international locations around the world.\" She voiced a character in the animated film ''My Dad Is Scrooge ''.<ref>{{cite web|title=MY DAD IS SCROOGE (90 min)|url=http://marvista.net/Details.aspx?id=ce76bf0d-74dc-e311-b063-d4ae527c3b65|accessdate=30 October 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141211150454/http://marvista.net/Details.aspx?id=ce76bf0d-74dc-e311-b063-d4ae527c3b65|archivedate=11 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nWright has completed Abigail Schwarz's comedy ''[[Those Who Wander]]'', produced by Nicola Scandiffio.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/thisisbwright/status/365766477040717824|title=Bonnie Wright Official, Verified Twitter Account (@thisisbwright)|publisher=Twitter.com|accessdate=7 November 2013}}</ref> and the adventure film ''Who Killed Nelson Nutmeg?''.<ref>{{cite web|author=Henry Hitchings|url=http://www.dorsetecho.co.uk/news/11542580.Harry_Potter_star_in_Dorset_to_shoot_new_film|title=Harry Potter star in Dorset to shoot new film|publisher=dorsetecho.co.uk|date=17 October 2014|accessdate=17 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, she signed on to co-star in [[Alexandra McGuinness]]'s thriller ''The Highway is for Gamblers'', with [[Nikki Reed]], [[Joe Jonas]], and [[Gustaf Skarsg\u00e5rd]]. The filming is scheduled to start in mid-November 2014 and is set in California's San Bernardino County.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Yamato|first1=Jen|title=Nikki Reed & Bonnie Wright Set For 'The Highway Is For Gamblers'|url=https://deadline.com/2014/10/nikki-reed-bonnie-wright-joe-jonas-the-highway-is-for-gamblers-845111/|website=Deadline.com|accessdate=27 October 2014|date=2014-10-02}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, it was announced that Wright will be the narrator of the ''Babbitty Rabbitty and her Cackling Stump'' story from the audiobook of ''[[The Tales of Beedle the Bard]]'', based on ''[[J.K.Rowling]]'' novel of the same title. The audiobook released on 31 March 2020, in aid of charity, called [[Lumos (charity)|Lumos]].<ref>[https://www.wizardingworld.com/news/beedle-the-bard-audiobook-announcement New audiobook The Tales of Beedle the Bard is coming soon] Wizardingworld.com. Retrieved on 26 February 2020.</ref>\n\n===Modelling===\nShe was named the winner of the ''Most Edgy Look Award'' at the 2011 ''Rodial Beautiful Awards''.<ref name=\"Rodial.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rodial.co.uk/about/articles/rodial_beautiful_awards.aspx |title=Rodial.co.uk |publisher=Rodial.co.uk |date= |accessdate=19 March 2011}}</ref> Also in 2011, Wright appeared in a fashion spread for ''[[The Financial Times]]''' luxury lifestyle magazine ''[[How to Spend It]]''. The shoot, which took place at the [[Victoria and Albert Museum]], was dedicated to capturing the languor of [[Dante Rossetti]]'s paintings.<ref>[[Anelli, Melissa]] (20 February 2011). [http://www.the-leaky-cauldron.org/2011/02/20/bonnie-wright-photoshoot-for-financial-times-how-to-spend-it-magazine/ \"Bonnie Wright-Photoshoot for Financial Times' 'How To Spend It' Magazine\"]. [[The Leaky Cauldron (website)|The Leaky Cauldron]].</ref>\n\nWright participated as a catwalk model for fashion designer Katie Eary at an Autumn/Winter 2011 show during [[London Fashion Week]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.refinery29.com/en-us/harry-potter-s-girlfriend-walked-the-runway-at-london-fashion-week|title=Ginny Weasley Walked In A Fashion Week Runway Show|first=Gabriel|last=Bell|website=refinery29.com}}</ref> In August 2013, Wright participated, along with ''Phoebe Collings James'' and ''Clara Paget'', who teamed up with jeweller designer ''Dominic Jones'' modelling southsea deckchairs in aid of ''World Land Trust'' and ''Winchester School of Art'' charity.<ref>[http://so-bonnie.net/wpress/2013/08/bonnie-models-southsea-deckchairs-for-charity/ Bonnie Wright Models Southsea Deckchairs For Charity] So.Bonnie.net</ref><ref>[http://www.vogue.co.uk/blogs/the-green-style-blog/2013/world-land-trust World Land Trust] Vogue UK</ref>\n\n===Screenwriting, directing and producing===\nWright made her screenwriting and directorial debut for her graduation film ''[[Separate We Come, Separate We Go]]'' starring her Harry Potter co-star [[David Thewlis]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.separatewecomeseparatewego.com|title=Separate We Come, Separate We Go|accessdate=28 March 2012}}</ref> The film premiered at the Cannes Film Festival short film corner and screen at the BAFTA Graduate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://registration.cannescourtmetrage.com/filmfiche2.Aspx?id=54996175|title=Catalogue|access-date=19 April 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130528162747/http://registration.cannescourtmetrage.com/filmfiche2.Aspx?id=54996175|archive-date=28 May 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.separatewecomeseparatewego.com|title=Separate We Come, Separate We Go|accessdate=1 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nWright has her own production company, Bon Bon Lumiere.<ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/profiles/4SJHNgGrz9yyz2jRt5qMBPW/bonnie-wright \"Bonnie Wright\"]. [[BBC]]. Retrieved 6 September 2014.</ref>\n\nIn December 2013, Wright directed her ''After the Dark'' co-star [[Sophie Lowe]], in her music video \"Dreaming\". The video was shot across [[Joshua Tree National Park]]. They filmed the video without any help, in the car of Lowe's friend. Wright filmed Lowe from the front seat of the car while Lowe was sitting in the back seat trying to create the feeling of drifting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nowness.com/day/2013/12/17/3542|title=Riding Solo|accessdate=30 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://thepermanentrainpress.com/post/70956446378|title=SOPHIE LOWE RELEASES NEW EP, \"DREAMING\" MUSIC VIDEO|accessdate=30 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2014, Wright wrote and directed another short film ''Know Thyself'', starring her ''Harry Potter'' co-star [[Christian Coulson]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elleuk.com/star-style/news/bonnie-wright-harry-potter-ginny-weasley-know-thyself-short-film#image=1|title=ELLE Reviews Know Thyself|accessdate=13 July 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140715034632/http://www.elleuk.com/star-style/news/bonnie-wright-harry-potter-ginny-weasley-know-thyself-short-film#image=1|archive-date=15 July 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2014, Wright directed the short film ''Fade to Gold'' for her jewellery-designer parents, Gary Wright and Sheila Teague, from Wright and Teague and LoveGold. The film showcases her parents' creative design of their jewellery, and there was a competition to win Wright's favourite pieces of Wright and Teague's jewellery.<ref>[http://www.lovegold.com/tags/contributor/bonnie-wright?itempath=/user/lovegold/post/7577 Wright & Teague: Fade to Gold by Bonnie Wright], Lovegold.com; retrieved 7 August 2014.</ref><ref>[http://so-bonnie.net/wpress/2014/07/bonnies-new-short-film-fade-to-gold-put-online Bonnie's new short film \u2018Fade to Gold\u2019 put online], So.Bonnie.net; retrieved 7 August 2014.</ref>\n\nIn January 2016, Wright made an announcement on her verified [[Twitter]] account that her next directorial project is ''Medusa's Ankles'', a short story by author [[A. S. Byatt]].<ref>[https://twitter.com/thisisbwright/status/689358917420322818 Bonnie Wright (@thisisbwright) on Twitter]; retrieved 19 January 2016.</ref>\n\nIn February 2016, she announced on her verified [[Twitter]] account that the ''Know Thyself'' film would premiere at the ''New Film Makers New York'' at the ''Anthology Film Archive'' on 10 February 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/thisisbwright/status/695003381388201985|title=Next Wed Feb10th my film Know Thyself is screening @NewFilmmakersNY program at @AnthologyFilm in New York http://www.newfilmmakers.com|first=Bonnie|last=Wright|date=3 February 2016|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n== Activism, charity and environmental work ==\n\nWright plays an active role in raising awareness around plastic pollution, particularly how it pollutes our oceans. In November 2017, she joined [[Greenpeace]] on their ship [[MV Arctic Sunrise|Arctic Sunrise]], monitoring plastic waste in the oceans, and in January 2018 she visited the [[Coca-Cola headquarters|Coca-Cola Headquarters]] in Atlanta, Georgia, to hand-deliver a petition to urge them to stop producing single-use plastic. She has held public discussions on how the every-day person can reduce single-use plastic usage, and is active in advocating for these changes on her Instagram page. \u201cEvery piece of plastic I have ever used is still somewhere on this earth, and that\u2019s terrifying,\u201d says Wright.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.peacefuldumpling.com/bonnie-wright|title=Bonnie Wright Wants Muggles, Not Magic, To Fix Plastic Crisis--Her Eco Chic Decoded|date=2018-03-27|website=Peaceful Dumpling|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-08}}</ref>\n\nWright is ambassador for a charity, called [[Lumos (charity)|Lumos]], which was founder in 2005 by Lumos Founder and Life President [[J.K.Rowling]]. In 2016, Wright and her fellow Lumos ambassador and Harry Potter co-star [[Evanna Lynch]], travelled to Haiti to learn about why there are 30,000 children living in orphanages, and met children who had been rescued from terrible conditions and reunited with their families. Wright spoken about Lumos's charity work, ''I\u2019d heard so much about the work that Lumos was doing and what exactly these institutions were like, but this experience highlighted how incredibly important Lumos\u2019 work is in Haiti.''<ref>[https://www.wearelumos.org/who-we-are/ambassadors/ Our Ambassadors] We Are Lumos.org. Retrieved 9 April 2020.</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nWright confirmed she was dating fellow ''Harry Potter'' actor [[Jamie Campbell Bower]] in February 2010, and their engagement in April 2011.<ref name=\"movies.ie\">{{cite interview |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_-85Jh0IJ34 |title=Bonnie Wright (Ginny Weasley) talks HARRY POTTER & her engagement to Jamie Campbell Bower |work=Movies Ireland |access-date=5 April 2011 |date=12 November 2010 |first=Bonnie |last=Wright}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.usmagazine.com/healthylifestyle/news/harry-potters-jamie-campbell-bower-bonnie-wright-engaged-2011134 |title=Harry Potter's Jamie Campbell Bower, Bonnie Wright Engaged! |magazine=[[US Weekly]] |date=13 April 2011 |access-date=27 October 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111025223206/http://www.usmagazine.com/healthylifestyle/news/harry-potters-jamie-campbell-bower-bonnie-wright-engaged-2011134 |archive-date=25 October 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> Wright and Bower called off their engagement on 30 June 2012.<ref>{{cite web |last=Ewart |first=Paul |title=Harry Potter: Where are they now? |date=10 January 2017 |work=[[News.com.au]] |url=http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/celebrity-life/harry-potter-where-are-they-now/news-story/8d8821ebb21dbff4e38f1ed8eb66d08b |access-date=30 May 2017 |publisher=News Pty Limited}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2001\n| ''[[Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone (film)|Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone]]''<!--DO NOT change to Sorcerer, the UK titles are used here-->\n| rowspan=\"8\" | [[Ginny Weasley]]\n|\n|-\n| 2002 \n| ''[[Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets (film)|Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets]]''\n|\n|-\n| 2004\n| ''[[Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban (film)|Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban]]''\n|\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''[[Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire (film)|Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire]]''\n|\n|-\n| 2007\n|''[[Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix (film)|Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix]]''\n|\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince (film)|Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince]]''\n|  \n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows&nbsp;\u2013 Part 1]]''\n|\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows&nbsp;\u2013 Part 2]]''\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | 2013\n| ''[[The Sea (2013 film)|The Sea]]''\n| Rose\n| <ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.rte.ie/ten/news/2013/0529/453372-edinburgh-premiere-for-banvilles-the-sea/|title=Edinburgh premiere for Banville's The Sea |newspaper=RT\u00c9 Ten |date=29 May 2013}}</ref><br />North American premiere ''[[2013 Toronto International Film Festival]]''<ref>{{cite web|title=Toronto International Film Festival \u2013 C