k of [[The Tales of Beedle the Bard]].<ref>[https://www.wizardingworld.com/news/beedle-the-bard-audiobook-announcement New audiobook The Tales of Beedle the Bard is coming soon] Wizardingworld.com. Retrieved on 26 February 2020.</ref>  \n|}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ Awards\n|-\n! Year\n! Award\n! Category\n! Film\n! Result\n|-\n|2011\n|Rodial Beautiful Awards<ref name=\"Rodial.co.uk\"/>\n|Most Edgy Look Award\n| ''[[Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows]]''\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|2012\n|[[Empire Award]]<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://www.empireonline.com/movies/news/jameson-empire-award-nominations-2012/ |title=The Awards Nominations Are Here! |first=Helen |last=O'Hara |journal=[[Empire Online]] |date=5 March 2012 |access-date=5 March 2012}}</ref>\n| Best Female Newcomer\n| ''[[Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows&nbsp;\u2013 Part 2]]''\n|{{nom}}\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Harry Potter films cast members]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Bonnie Wright}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*{{IMDb name|0942247}}\n*{{Twitter}}\n*{{cite news|url=https://www.ew.com/ew/gallery/0,,20290,736,00.html|title='Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince': 8 EW Exclusive Cast Pics |publisher=Entertainment Weekly |date=10 July 2009 |first=Jeff |last=Jenson |accessdate=13 June 2010}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.instyle.co.uk/news/instyle-celebrates-new-british-talent-27-01-10|title=InStyle celebrates new British talent |publisher=InStyle.co.uk |date=27 January 2010 |first=Pat |last=McNulty |accessdate=13 June 2010}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wright, Bonnie}}\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Actresses from London]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of the Arts London]]\n[[Category:English child actresses]]\n[[Category:English film actresses]]\n[[Category:English television actresses]]\n[[Category:English voice actresses]]\n[[Category:People educated at King Alfred School, London]]\n[[Category:21st-century English actresses]]\n[[Category:English female models]]\n[[Category:English music video directors]]\n[[Category:English film directors]]\n", "name_user": "Nightscream", "label": "safe", "comment": "spacing", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bonnie_Wright"}
{"title_page": "Sampson Mathews", "text_new": "{{good article}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name= Sampson Mathews\n|image= Sampson(2).jpg\n|caption=Silhouette of Sampson Mathews, 1756 <ref>{{cite book |last=Clem |first=Gladys |author-link= |date=1965 |title=It Happened Around Staunton in Virginia |url=https://books.google.com/?id=zYHhAAAAMAAJ |location=Augusta County, Virginia |publisher=McClure Print Company |page=21\u201323 |isbn=|oclc=3512763}}</ref>\n|alt=\n|order=\n|office= [[Virginia State Senate|Virginia State Senator]] from Augusta, Rockingham, Rockbridge, Shenandoah, and Pendleton counties\n|term= 1776\u20131780, 1790\n|predecessor =\n|successor = \n|lieutenant= \n|birth_date= c. 1737\n|birth_place= [[Augusta County, Virginia|Augusta County]],[[Colony of Virginia|Virginia]], [[British America]]\n|death_date= January 20, 1807 (aged 70)\n|death_place= [[Staunton, Virginia]], U.S.\n|spouse= Mary Lockhart<br>Mary Warwick\n|children= John<br>Sampson II<br>Two daughters<br>Martha (guardian ''ad litem'')\n|parents=[[John Mathews (American pioneer)|John Mathews]]<br>Ann Mathews\n|party= \n|religion= Presbyterian<ref>[[#Grigsby|Grigsby]], p. 88</ref>\n|relatives = [[Mathews family]]\n|profession    = merchant, soldier, politician\n|signature=Sampson Mathews signature, library of congress.png\n|signature_alt=\n|office2=\n|term_start2=\n|term_end2=\n|order3 =\n|term3 =\n|rank= [[File:US-O5 insignia.svg|30px]] [[Lieutenant colonel (United States)|Lieutenant Colonel]] of Virginia militia\n|allegiance= {{flagicon|Kingdom of Great Britain}} [[Kingdom of Great Britain|Great Britain]]<br>{{flagicon|United States of America|1777}} [[United States]]\n|branch= [[Virginia militia|Virginia provincial militia]]<br>Virginia militia\n|serviceyears= 1755-1774 (colonial forces)<br>1778-1783 (U.S. forces)\n|unit= \n|battles =French and Indian War<br>{{*}}[[Braddock expedition]]<br>Dunmore's War<br>{{*}}[[Battle of Point Pleasant]]<br>American Revolutionary War<br>{{*}}[[Raid of Richmond]]<br>{{*}}[[Battle of Green Spring]]<br>{{*}}[[Siege of Yorktown]]\n|awards=\n}}\n\n'''Sampson Mathews''' (c. 1737 \u2013 January 20, 1807) was an [[United States|American]] merchant, soldier, and legislator in the colony (and later U.S. state) of [[Virginia]].\n\nA son of John and Ann (Archer) Mathews, Mathews was an early merchant in the [[Shenandoah Valley]] region, where he and his brother [[George Mathews (Georgia)|George Mathews]] ran a series of mercantile outposts that extended to Atlantic trade networks. As war came to the colonies, Mathews took part in the [[Indian Wars]] and colonial revolutionary efforts. He was a member of the Augusta County [[Committee of Safety (American Revolution)|Committee of Safety]] that drafted the [[Augusta Resolves]], a precursor to the [[United States Declaration of Independence|Declaration of Independence]], and the [[Augusta Declaration]], a precursor to the [[Model Treaty]] (foreign policy), and the [[Articles of Confederation]] (the first U.S. constitution). \n\nMathews was elected to the inaugural [[Virginia State Senate]] in 1776. During the [[American Revolution]], he toured the [[American frontier|western frontier]] to fortify the colonial border from Indian attacks, and oversaw sail manufacture for the [[Continental Navy]]'s Virginia fleet. When turncoat [[Benedict Arnold]] enacted a surprise [[raid of Richmond]] in January 1781, Mathews lead Virginia militia forces in defense.\n\nMathews was an original [[trustee]] of Liberty Hall (later [[Washington and Lee University]]), when it was made into a college in 1776. This is the nation's ninth oldest institution of higher education. Mathews was a member of the [[Mathews family|Mathews political family]], which saw numerous members take part in state and national affairs over successive generations.\n\n\n== Early life and Indian Wars==\n{{See also|Mathews family}}\nSampson Mathews was born c. 1737 in [[Augusta County, Virginia]] to Ann (Archer) and [[John Mathews (American pioneer)|John Mathews]]. His parents were among the first settlers of Augusta County, likely having immigrated to America during the [[Scotch-Irish American|Scotch-Irish]] immigration of 1710\u20131775.<ref>[[#Waddell|Waddell]], p. 1</ref> His father was a notable member of the early Augusta County community, serving as a militia captain and public officer.<ref>[[#Peyton|Peyton]], p. 97</ref><ref>[[#Waddell|Waddell]], p. 137</ref> Sampson Mathews was educated at the Augusta Academy, a classical school founded in 1749.<ref>[[#Grigsby|Grigsby]], p. 88</ref> In his adolescence he worked in various crews to build roads in the county.<ref>[[#Chalkley|Chalkley]], p. 61\u201362</ref>\n\nOn the outbreak of the [[French and Indian War]] in 1755, Mathews was elected captain in the Augusta County militia,<ref>[[#Chalkley|Chalkley]], p. 183</ref> and accompanied [[George Washington]] under British General [[Edward Braddock]] on his ill-fated [[Braddock expedition]]. Up to four of Mathews' siblings, as well as his father, also took part in the expedition.<ref>[[#Henning|Henning]], p. 195</ref> Braddock's expedition met with the French and Indians in a [[meeting engagement]], from which the French and Indians gained the advantage. After suffering devastating casualties, the British retreated in disarray.<ref>{{cite book |last=Boreman |first=Walter R. |author-link= |date=2007 |title=The French and Indian War |url= |location=New York |publisher=Rutgers |page=55 |isbn=978-0-06-076185-1}}</ref> \n\nOn returning home, Mathews was elected [[sheriff]] of Augusta County in 1756, and also assumed the functions of [[chancellor]] of the county.<ref>[[#Waddell|Waddell]], p. 77</ref> For a time he worked as a reader for the local church, though this was apparently suspended due to a thinning of the population following the French and Indian War.<ref>[[#Waddell|Waddell]], p. 147</ref> Mathews married Mary Lockhart in 1759,<ref>[[#Morton|Morton]], p. 163</ref> with whom he had four children: John, Sampson, and two daughters who went on to be Mrs. Samuel Clark and Mrs. Alexander Nelson.<ref>[[#Waddell|Waddell]], p. 310</ref> By 1762, Mathews and his brother [[George Mathews (Georgia)|George Mathews]] had gone into a mercantile business in [[Staunton, Virginia]]. Quick success lead them to open numerous other stores and outposts in the Upper Valley, and to accumulate thousands of acres of land in the region.<ref>[[#Morton|Morton]], p. 162</ref> In their outposts they sold basic supplies but also specialty items including \"spelling books, silk, hats, \u201cozgn\u201d, handkerchiefs, silver, and even a tailor-made suit,\" and acted as unofficial bankers.<ref>{{cite journal |last1= Handley|first1=Harry |date=1963 |title=The Mathews Trading Post |url= http://gillilandtrails.org/documents/bios/bio_MathewsTradingPost.pdf|journal=The Journal of the Greenbrier Historical Society |volume= 1|issue=1 |pages= |doi= |access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref> Their enterprise grew to involve an extensive Atlantic trade network.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.georgiaencyclopedia.org/articles/government-politics/george-mathews-1739-1812 |title=George Mathews (1739\u20131812) |last=Ebel |first= Carol|date=2003 |website=New Georgia Encyclopedia |publisher=Georgia Humanities and the University of Georgia Press |access-date=April 16, 2020 |quote=}}</ref> The brothers imported and sold [[penal transportation|convict servants]] from Britain,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.vcdh.virginia.edu/gos/countyRecords/relatedAd.php?adFile=sg73.xml&adId=v1773111875 |title=Virginia Gazette, Williamsburg, November 11, 1773. |last= |first= |date= |website=The Geography of Slavery in Virginia |publisher=University of Virginia |access-date=April 16, 2020 |quote=}}</ref> and a small number of African slaves.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Herndon|first1=G. Melvin|title=George Mathews, Frontier Patriot|journal=Virginia Magazine of History and Biography|date=1969|volume=77|issue=3|page=310|jstor=4247487}}</ref> In total, their dealings accounted for a \"great share\" of the trade in the region.<ref>{{cite book| last1=Van Schreeven| first1= William| last2=Scribner| first2= Robert| last3=Tarter| first3= Brent| author-link =  | year=1973| title=Revolutionary Virginia, the road to independence, vol. 5. Independence and the Fifth convention| publisher= University Press of Virginia | location = [[Charlottesville, Virginia]] | isbn= | oclc = 802770| url= |accessdate=|ref=Van Schreeven et al.}}</ref>\n\nMathews was appointed a [[justice of the peace]] for Augusta County in 1764, and in that role he presided over [[misdemeanors]] and other civil cases in the county.<ref>[[#Waddell2|Waddell2]], p. 439</ref> He also served as a member of the [[Vestryman|vestry]] for Augusta Parish around this time,<ref>[[#Waddell|Waddell]], p. 167</ref> with the vestry being the ''[[de facto]]'' local government for the county.<ref>[[#Peyton|Peyton]], p. 97</ref> Mathews was granted a [[liquor license]] in 1765,<ref>[[#Chalkley|Chalkley]], p. 122</ref> and his tavern and inn in Staunton, a \"long frame building, a story and a half high, with [[dormer]] windows,\"<ref>[[#Waddell|Waddell]], p. 166</ref> soon became the most fashionable of its kind in Staunton.<ref>[[#Morton|Morton]], p. 163</ref> In 1768, Mathews became the guardian ''ad litem'' for a niece, Martha Mathews, on the premature death of her father, Joshua Mathews. <ref>[[#Chalkley|Chalkley]], p. 149</ref> She would later marry [[Thomas Posey]], whose father had been a guest at Mathews' inn and probably arranged their meeting.<ref name=Posey>Posey, John Thornton.  ''General Thomas Posey: Son of the American Revolution.'' East Lansing, MI: Michigan State University Press, 1992. Pages 17\u201318 {{ISBN|0-87013-316-0}}</ref> \n\nIn 1773, Mathews and others solicited subscriptions for a new academy in the Valley. This academy, named Liberty Hall and located in [[Lexington, Virginia]], was officially incorporated by the Commonwealth of Virginia in 1782, with Mathews serving as an original trustee.<ref>[[#Grigsby|Grigsby]], p. 87</ref> Liberty Hall was eventually renamed [[Washington and Lee University]],<ref>[[#Waddell|Waddell]], p. 303</ref> and is the nation's ninth oldest institution of higher education.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://my.wlu.edu/about-wandl/history-and-traditions/a-brief-history |title=A Brief History |last= |first= |date= |website=Washington & Lee University |publisher=Washington & Lee University |access-date=April 16, 2020 |quote=}}</ref>\n\nIn fall of 1774, [[List of colonial governors of Virginia|Royal Governor]] [[Lord Dunmore]] assembled a 1000-man invasion of Indian territory, culling recruits from Augusta County. Mathews' tavern served as headquarters for the local militia during preparations. A possibly [[apocryphal]] story arose that the men of George Mathews' regiment marked their height on a wall of Sampson Mathews' tavern, revealing that all but two men were over six feet tall.<ref>[[#Waddell|Waddell]], p. 220\u2013221</ref> For the expedition, Mathews served as [[chief procurement officer]] for General [[Andrew Lewis (soldier)|Andrew Lewis]], and oversaw the driving of 500 pack horses, 54,000 pounds of flour, and 108 cattle for the march from Augusta to [[Point Pleasant, West Virginia|Point Pleasant]], for which the troops gave him the nickname \"Master Driver of Cattle.\"<ref>[[#Waddell|Waddell]], p. 220</ref> An early Ohio historian said of Mathews' march:\n{{Quote\n|His route lay wholly through a trackless forest. All his baggage, his provisions, and even his ammunition, had to be transported on pack-horses, that were clambering about among tall cliffs, or winding their way among dangerous defiles, ascending or descending the lofty summits of the Alleghenies. . . During nineteen entire days, this gallant band pressed forward descending from the height of the Allegheny mountains to the mouth of the Kenawha [sic], a distance of one hundred and sixty miles.<ref>{{cite book |last=Lewis |first=Virgil |author-link= |date=1909 |title=History of the Battle of Point Pleasant Fought Between White Men and Indians at the Mouth of the Great Kanawha River (now Point Pleasant, West Virginia) Monday, October 10th, 1774 |url= |location=Charleston, West Virginia |publisher=Tribune Printing Company |page=31 |isbn=1888265590}}</ref>}}\n\nOctober 10, 1774,  The [[Battle of Point Pleasant]] was fought between the Virginia militia and Indians from the [[Shawnee]] and [[Mingo]] tribes along the [[Ohio River]]. Various sources credit either [[Colonel (United Kingdom)|Colonel]] [[Andrew Lewis (soldier)|Andrew Lewis]] or [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|Captain]] George Mathews with a flanking maneuver that initiated [[Shawnee]] Chief [[Cornstalk]]'s retreat and secured victory for the colonial militia.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Herndon|first1=G. Melvin|title=George Mathews, Frontier Patriot|journal=Virginia Magazine of History and Biography|date=1969|volume=77|issue=3|page=312|jstor=4247487}}</ref>\n\n== American Revolution ==\nThe months following the Dunmore's War saw tension rise between the British and the colonies. The [[Virginia House of Burgesses]] began to resist the Crown, and in retaliation Lord Dunmore dissolved it in May 1774. This lead the Burgesses to form the extralegal [[Virginia Conventions]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.encyclopediavirginia.org/House_of_Burgesses#start_entry|title= House of Burgesses |last=Gottlieb|first=Matthew S. |publisher=Virginia Foundation of the Humanities|accessdate=April 16, 2020|ref=gottlieb}}</ref>\n\n===Revolutionary activities===\nOn February 22, 1775, Mathews took part in the first documented revolutionary meeting in Augusta County, as a member of the county's [[Committee of Safety (American Revolution)|Committee of Safety]].<ref>[[#Waddell|Waddell]], p. 235</ref> These county committees were an outgrowth of the Virginia [[Committee of Correspondence]], the state's patriotic shadow government. The Augusta County committee met in Staunton, Virginia, and drafted the [[Augusta Resolves]] to assert their county's commitment to \"enjoy the free exercise of conscience, and of human nature.\" The committee then elected delegates to the [[Second Virginia Convention]] in March 1775, with Mathews among those who drafted instructions for the delegates.<ref>[[#Waddell|Waddell]], p. 235</ref> The Augusta Resolves were endorsed in a meeting of [[freehold (law)|freeholders]] of Augusta County and published in Pinkney's March 16, 1775 [[Virginia Gazette]]. Historian Jim Glanville states that the resolutions of Virginia's four western counties (Augusta, Botetourt, [[Fincastle Resolutions|Fincastle]], and Pittsylvania) are best viewed as a whole and were \"by far the most significant statements in favor of American liberty\" of the county resolutions that were a direct precursor to the [[Declaration of Independence]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1= Glanville|first1=Jim |date=2010 |title=The Fincastle Resolutions |url=https://vtechworks.lib.vt.edu/bitstream/handle/10919/88172/SR_v14_glanville.pdf?sequence=1&isAllowed=y |journal=The Smithfield Review |volume=XIV |issue= |pages=78 |doi= |access-date=April 16, 2020 }}</ref>\n\nMathews, with two other representatives of the Augusta County committee, met with members of the counties of [[Albemarle County, Virginia|Albemarle]], [[Amherst County, Virginia|Amherst]], and [[Buckingham County, Virginia|Buckingham]] in September 1775 to organize militia units in preparation for war against Britain. Augusta County resolved to raise four companies of fifty men each, with the other counties raising two companies of fifty men each. George Mathews was given command of the ten companies.<ref>[[#Waddell|Waddell]], p. 245</ref>\n{{quote box\n |quote  = \"It [the Augusta Declaration] is the first deliberate expression of the policy of establishing an independent state government and a permanent confederation of the States which our parliamentary journals contain. . .This memorial from Augusta . . .deserves to be stereotyped as the Magna Charta of the West.\"<ref>[[#Grigsby|Grigsby 1890(2)]], p. 66</ref>\n |source = - [[Hugh Blair Grigsby]], ''Washington and Lee University Historical Papers, Volumes 1\u20132 (1890)''\n |width  = 35%\n |align  = right\n}}\nBy the time of the [[Fifth Virginia Convention]] in May 1776, many its delegates knew the issue of independence would be addressed, and some came with prepared statements on the subject.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Dunaway, Jr. |first1=W.F. |date=1904 |title= The Virginia Conventions of the Revolution |journal=Virginia Law Register |volume=10 |issue=7 |pages=581 |doi= 10.2307/1100650|jstor=1100650 }}</ref> However, over the first several sessions, the Convention dealt with matters largely related to the ongoing war effort.<ref>{{cite book| last1=Van Schreeven| first1= William| last2=Scribner| first2= Robert| last3=Tarter| first3= Brent| author-link =  | year=1973| title=Revolutionary Virginia, the road to independence, vol. 7. Independence and the Fifth convention| publisher= University Press of Virginia | location = [[Charlottesville, Virginia]] | isbn= | oclc = 802770| url= | accessdate=|page= p. 124, n. 3|ref=Van Schreeven et al.}}</ref> On May 10, 1776, [[Thomas Lewis (Virginia)|Thomas Lewis]] broached the independence issue when, on behalf of the Augusta County Committee of Safety, he introduced the [[Augusta Declaration]] to the Convention. This was the first official proposal for the creation of a permanent and independent union of states and national government from any of the Thirteen Colonies. Virginia history scholar [[Hugh Blair Grigsby]] states the Augusta Declaration \"deserves to be stereotyped as the [[Magna Charta]] of the West\" for its precedent in calling for this governmental mode, which was adopted in the creation of the United States of America.<ref>[[#Grigsby|Grigsby]], p. 66</ref> The  proposals for independence, a confederation of colonies, and a national government were passed by the Virginia Convention on March 15 and forwarded to the [[Second Continental Congress]],<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/patrickhenrylif00henrgoog/page/n14|title=Patrick Henry; Life, Correspondence and Speeches|first=William Wirt|last=Henry|authorlink=William Wirt Henry|page=401|publisher=Charles Scribner's Sons|location= [[New York, New York]]|year=1891| oclc = 727087|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref> which then initiated the drafting of the Declaration of Independence, the [[Articles of Confederation]], and the [[Model Treaty]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://history.state.gov/milestones/1776-1783/model-treaty |title=The Model Treaty, 1776 |last= |first= |date= |website= United States Office of the Historian |publisher= United States Dept. of State|access-date=April 19, 2020 |quote=}}</ref>\n\n===Virginia State Senate and war efforts===\n\nMathews was elected to the [[Virginia State Senate]], the successor to the [[Virginia Governor's Council]], for its inaugural session of 1776, representing Augusta and [[Shenandoah County, Virginia|Dunmore]] counties. He remained a member of the state senate through 1780, representing Augusta, [[Rockingham County, Virginia|Rockingham]], [[Rockbridge County, Virginia|Rockbridge]], and [[Shenandoah County, Virginia|Shenandoah]] counties from 1778\u20131780.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://vavh.electionstats.com/php/bio.php?pid=4813 |title=The Virginia Elections and State Elected Officials Database Project, 1776-2007 |last=Kromkowski |first= C. |date=2005 |website=The Virginia Elections and State Elected Officials Database Project, 1776\u20132007 |publisher=University of Virginia Library |access-date=April 16, 2020 |quote=|ref=Kromkowski}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote box\n |quote  = Of the public rope-walks, manufactories of ducking, sail-cloth, etc, the most important was that at Warwick on the James, five miles south of Richmond. Skilled sail-makers were probably drawn from the Ulster settlement in the Valley of Virginia, some of whose members had doubtless served an apprenticeship in Ireland. The assignment of Col. Sampson Mathews, of August County, to a committee on the supervision of naval equipment is not without significance.<ref>{{cite book |last=Stewart |first=Robert A. |author-link= |date=1934 |title=The History of Virginia's Navy of the Revolution |url= |location=Charlottesville, Virginia |publisher=Mitchell & Hotchkiss |page=136 |isbn=\t9780806348711}}</ref>\n |source = --Robert Armistead Stewart, ''The History of Virginia's Navy of the Revolution'' (1934).\n |width  = 35%\n |align  = right\n}}\n\nDuring its inaugural session, the senate sought to promote the [[Continental Navy]]'s Virginia fleet. At this time, Virginia had more land and manufactories devoted to naval purposes than any of the colonies, but it faced a distinct lack of materials needed to create linen sail cloth. Mathews, along with Alexander St. Clair, was therefore appointed to erect and superintend a factory in Staunton, Virginia for the making of sail material from flax grown by Augusta County farmers.<ref>[[#Waddell|Waddell]], p. 251</ref>\n\nHowever, other matters soon drew Mathews elsewhere. In the fall of 1777, Shawnee Chief Cornstalk made a diplomatic visit to the American [[Fort Randolph (West Virginia)|Fort Randolph]], on the site present-day [[Point Pleasant, West Virginia]]. Virginia militiamen took Cornstalk hostage at the fort, and on November 10, 1777, killed him without cause.<ref>[[#Tillson|Tillson]], p. 141\u2013142</ref> This lead to an immediate backlash from the Shawnee. Congress, sensing the urgency of the situation, passed a resolution on November 20 to send commissioners out west with the aim of restoring friendly relations between the Shawnee and the colonists that had been years in the making. Mathews was appointed to represent Virginia, and [[George Clymer]] for Pennsylvania. The men arrived at [[Fort Pitt (Pennsylvania)|Fort Pitt]] in mid-March, and reported back to Congress in late-April that the British in Detroit were aiding the Shawnee and nearby Delaware tribes in their attacks. Further, they believed the colonists may well be able to restore friendly relations with the Indians by capturing [[Fort Detroit]] from the British, and thus weakening the Indians' position.<ref>{{cite journal |last1= Bushnell|first1=David |date=1924 |title= The Proposed Expedition against Detroit, 1778|journal=The Virginia Magazine of History and Biography |volume=32 |issue=1 |pages=66 |doi= |jstor=4243948 |ref=Bushnell}}</ref> They proposed a force of 3,000 be dedicated to this cause.<ref>{{cite book |last=Pieper |first=Thomas |author-link= |date=1980 |title=Fort Laurens, 1778-1779: The Revolutionary War in Ohio |url=https://books.google.com/?id=9aoJVOjymwIC&dq=%22sampson+matthews%22 |location= |publisher=Kent State University Press |page=13 |isbn=9780873382403}}</ref> Congress, however, deferred the recommendation, considering it too costly, and instead sent troops to fortify their western borders.<ref>[[#Bushnell|Bushnell]]</ref>\n\n===Military service===\n{{Main article|Raid of Richmond}}\n[[File:Benedict Arnold. Copy of engraving by H. B. Hall after John Trumbull, published 1879., 1931 - 1932 - NARA - 532921.tif|thumb|upright=1.0|left|British Brigadier General [[Benedict Arnold]] invaded Virginia by surprise in 1781.]]\nMathews was appointed [[Lieutenant colonel (United States)|lieutenant colonel]] of Augusta County militia in May 1778,<ref>[[#Chalkley|Chalkley]], p. 197</ref> giving him command of the county militia and a field commission of [[Colonel (United States)|colonel]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |title=Virginia's Soldiers in the Revolution (Continued) |journal=The Virginia Magazine of History and Biography |year= 1914|volume=22 |issue=1 |pages=57-67 (58) |doi= |jstor= 4243322}}</ref> This was a position normally given to the most prominent leader of the county.<ref>[[#Tillson|Tillson]], p. 47</ref> Mathews called out the militia for a three month tour in April 1779, on account of Indian threats in [[Tygart Valley River|Tygart Valley, Virginia]].<ref>[[#McCallister|McCallister]], p. 105</ref> The expedition resulted in several scouting missions, but no battle. <ref>[[#Waddell|Waddell]], p. 258</ref> In October 1780, Mathews requested to disqualify himself form serving the rest of his term in the Virginia State Senate.<ref>[[#Chalkley|Chalkley]], p. 217</ref>\n\nOn January 1, 1781, British [[Brigadier (United Kingdom)|Brigadier General]] [[Benedict Arnold]] launched a surprise invasion of Virginia. For five days he sailed up the [[James River]] to virtually no resistance. Virginia Governor [[Thomas Jefferson]] fled the capitol of [[Richmond, Virginia|Richmond]] as Arnold approached, and Arnold thereafter burned and looted the city. Jefferson called out militia commanders throughout the state to help to repel Arnold's invasion. He directed Mathews to march to [[Fredericksburg, Virginia|Fredericksburg]],<ref>[[#Waddell|Waddell]], p. 278\u2013279</ref> and report to [[Brigadier general (United States)|Brigadier General]] [[George Weedon]]. Mathews wrote to the governor the next day, confirming that he and a company of 250 would head to Fredericksburg in the morning. Mathews also recruited his son-in-law [[Major (United States)|Major]] Thomas Posey to join him with his troops for the march.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://founders.archives.gov/documents/Jefferson/01-04-02-0432 |title=To Thomas Jefferson from Sampson Mathews, 13 January 1781 |last= |first= |date= |website=Founders Online |publisher=National Archives |access-date=2020-04-10 |quote=I have Prevailed with Major Posey to go with me who will be of great Service.}}</ref><ref>[[#Waddell|Waddell]], p. 279, p. 310</ref>\n\nMathews made the approximately 100 mile march from Staunton to Fredericksburg in four days. After spending an additional four days in Fredericksburg, Mathews was directed by [[Major General (United States)|Major General]] [[Peter Muhlenberg]] to turn to [[Bowling Green, Virginia|Bowling Green]] about 30 miles south. There Mathews wrote to Jefferson urging that he make materials available \"for the repair of the arms of the militia.\"\n<ref>{{cite web |url=https://founders.archives.gov/documents/Jefferson/01-04-02-0523 |title=From Sampson Mathews, with Jefferson's Instructions to George Muter, 21 January 1781 |last= |first= |date= |website=Founders Online |publisher=National Archives |access-date=April 16, 2020 |quote=The Bearer Mr. Chas. Cocke will wait on your Excellency For an order For these articles which are very much wanting.}}</ref> Muhlenberg then directed Mathews to [[Cabin Point, Virginia|Cabin Point]] in [[Smithfield, Virginia]], some 80 miles southeast to the mouth of the James. Mathews wrote to Jefferson on the 29th that his march had been delayed at the James River for several days due to poor weather and insufficiency of the transport boats. He described the lack of basic provisions in his camp, including tents and ammunition, and the poor health of many from exposure to the winter elements, which lead him to fear mutiny.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://founders.archives.gov/documents/Jefferson/01-04-02-0574 |title=To Thomas Jefferson from Sampson Mathews, 29 January 1781 |last= |first= |date= |website=Founders Online |publisher=National Archives |access-date=April 16, 2020 |quote=Is afraid the men will mutiny because the \u201cmarch is So Severe\u201d and the \u201cduty on the Lines will add To the fatigue.\u201d}}</ref><ref>[[#Waddell|Waddell]], p. 279</ref>\n\nJefferson responded on the 31st, relaying that there were some 150 tents \"somewhere,\" and that he would attempt locate and direct them toward Mathews, acknowledging that Mathews' position \"nearest the enemy's lines\" validated the expediency of these supplies.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://founders.archives.gov/documents/Jefferson/01-04-02-0594 |title=From Thomas Jefferson to Sampson Mathews and John Bowyer, 31 January 1781 |last= |first= |date= |website=Founders Online |publisher=National Archives |access-date=April 16, 2020 |quote= I have given orders to find in whose possession they are, and as soon as it is known I will inform Baron Steuben and communicate to him your want,...}}</ref> By the 15th of February, the Virginia militia had bottled up Arnold's forces in [[Portsmouth, Virginia]], with Mathews commanding the advanced post alongside 350 riflemen.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://founders.archives.gov/documents/Jefferson/01-04-02-0776 |title=To Thomas Jefferson from Robert Lawson, 15 February 1781 |last= |first= |date= |website=Founders Online |publisher=National Archives |access-date=April 16, 2020 |quote=}}</ref><ref>[[#Waddell|Waddell]], p. 279\u2013280</ref> Nothing else is known of the Mathews' regiment during this expedition, and the Augusta County militia returned home in mid-April.<ref>[[#Waddell|Waddell]], p. 279</ref> \n\nThe Virginia General Assembly, having fled Arnold's force in Richmond, met in the [[Trinity Episcopal Church (Staunton, Virginia)|Trinity Episcopal Church]] in Staunton, Virginia from June 7 to 23. On June 12, the Assembly voted to elect [[Thomas Nelson Jr.]] as the [[List of governors of Virginia|4th governor of Virginia]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.encyclopediavirginia.org/The_Election_of_Thomas_Nelson_as_Governor_June_12_1781 |title=The Election of Governor Thomas Nelson |last= |first= |date= |website=Encyclopedia Virginia |publisher=Virginia Humanities |access-date=April 18, 2020 |quote=}}</ref> Mathews, who remained a justice of the peace for Augusta County, administered the [[oath of office]] to Nelson the following week, on June 19.<ref>[[#Chalkley|Chalkley]], p. 527</ref> Mathews quickly left again for eastern Virginia, bringing a regiment to [[James City, Virginia]] where it saw action in the [[Battle of Green Spring]].<ref>[[#Morton|Morton]], p. 95\u201396</ref> Mathews' field lieutenant colonel, William Boyer, was captured during the battle.<ref>[[#McCallister|McCallister], p. 64</ref>. On August 8,  Mathews went to [[Yorktown, Virginia]], where the [[Siege of Yorktown]] proved to be the last major battle of the war.<ref>[[#Waddell2|Waddell2]], p. 491</ref> By November 1781 Mathews had returned from battle and resumed his duties in the Virginia State Senate, being appointed to the Privy Council on November 30.<ref>{{cite book |last=Virginia General Assembly |author-link= |date=1828 |title=1781 Journal of the Virginia House of Delegates |url=https://archive.org/details/journalofhouseof178186virg/page/n57/mode/2up |location=Richmond, Virginia |publisher=Commonwealth of Virginia |page=23 |isbn=}}</ref> Mathews stepped down as lieutenant colonel of Augusta County militia on November 18, 1783.<ref>[[#Chalkley|Chalkley]], p. 233</ref>\n\n==Later life==\nMathews served a final term in the Virginia State Senate in 1790, representing Augusta, Rockingham, Rockbridge, Shenandoah, and [[Pendleton County, West Virginia|Pendleton]] counties.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://vavh.electionstats.com/php/bio.php?pid=4813 |title=The Virginia Elections and State Elected Officials Database Project, 1776-2007 |last=Kromkowski |first= C. |date=2005 |website=The Virginia Elections and State Elected Officials Database Project, 1776\u20132007 |publisher=University of Virginia Library |access-date=April 16, 2020 |quote=|ref=Kromkowski}}</ref> He then served as a justice of the peace and the first [[High Sheriff|high sheriff]] of [[Bath County, Virginia|Bath County]] when it was formed from Augusta County in 1791.<ref>[[#Morton|Morton]], p. 136</ref><ref>[[#Waddell2|Waddell2]], p. 481</ref> He also served as an original trustee for [[Hot Springs, Virginia]] on its formation in 1793.<ref>[[#Morton|Morton]], p. 47</ref> He lived in Bath County about ten years at his estate, Cloverdale.<ref>[[#Waddell|Waddell]], p. 344</ref> On the death of his wife Mary, he married again to a Mary Warwick.<ref>[[#Morton|Morton]], p. 163</ref> He resided in Staunton, Virginia in later life, in a log house at the intersection of Beverly and Water Streets. He died in Staunton in 1807.<ref>[[#Waddell|Waddell]], p. 310</ref>\n\nMathews' son, Sampson Mathews II, served as a Virginia Delegate from [[Bath County, Virginia|Bath County]] for the 1809\u20131810 session of the Virginia General Assembly, representing the [[Federalist party]].<ref>[[#Grigsby|Grigsby]], p. 88</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://vavh.electionstats.com/php/bio.php?pid=4805 |title=The Virginia Elections and State Elected Officials Database Project, 1776-2007 |last=Kromkowski |first= C. |date=2005 |website=The Virginia Elections and State Elected Officials Database Project, 1776-2007 |publisher=University of Virginia Library |access-date=April 16, 2020 |quote=|ref=}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book| last=Chalkley | first=Lyman| author-link =  | year=1912 | title=Chronicles of the Scotch-Irish Settlement in Virginia | publisher= The Commonwealth printing co | location = [[Rosslyn, Virginia]] |  isbn= | oclc = 2575649 | url= https://archive.org/details/chroniclesscotc00lockgoog/page/n6 | accessdate= |ref=Chalkley }}\n* {{cite book| last=Grigsby | first= Hugh Blair| author-link =Hugh Blair Grigsby  | year=1890 | title=Washington and Lee University Historical Papers, Volumes 1\u20132 | publisher= The New York Public Library |page=88 |location = [[Lexington, Virginia]] |  isbn= | oclc = | url= https://books.google.com/?id=9p4gAAAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage | accessdate=|ref=Grigsby}}\n* {{cite book| last=Henning | first=William W.| author-link =  | year=1809 | title=The Statutes at Large: Being a Collection of all the Laws of Virginia, vol. 7| publisher= R. & W. & G. Bartow | location = New York City |  isbn= | oclc = 426084215 | url= https://archive.org/details/statutesatlargeb07virg| accessdate= |ref=Henning }}\n* {{cite book |last=McCallister |first=J.T. |author-link= |date=1913 |title=Virginia militia in the Revolutionary War : McAllister's data |url=https://archive.org/details/militiaintherevolu00mcalrich/mode/2up |location=Hot Springs, Virginia |publisher=McCallister Publishing Co. |page= |isbn=|oclc=1536303|ref=McCallister}}\n* {{cite book| last=Morton | first=Oren| author-link = | year=1978| title= Annals of Bath County, Virginia | publisher= C.J. Carrier Co.| location = [[Harrisonburg, Virginia]] |  isbn= | oclc = 656749557 | url= https://archive.org/details/annalsofbathcoun00mort/ | accessdate=April 17, 2020 |ref=Morton }}\n* {{cite book| last=Peyton | first=John L. | author-link =  | year=1882 | title=History of Augusta County, Virginia| publisher= Samuel M. Yost & son | location = Unknown |  isbn= 1230356312 | oclc = 923774044 | url= https://archive.org/details/historyaugustac00peytgoog| accessdate= |ref=Peyton }}\n* {{cite book |last=Tillson, Jr. |first=Albert |author-link= |date=1991 |title=Gentry and Common Folk: Political Culture on a Virginia Frontier 1740\u20131789 |url=https://uknowledge.uky.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1084&context=upk_united_states_history |location=Lexington, KY |publisher=The University Press of Kentucky |page= |isbn=9780813155173}}\n* {{cite book| last=Waddell | first=Joseph A. | author-link =  | year=1902 | title=Annals of Augusta County, Virginia, from 1726 to 1871 | publisher= C. R. Caldwell | location = [[Staunton, Virginia]] | isbn= | oclc = 3880311| url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_rZbEC1kEdpcC | accessdate=|ref=Waddell }}\n* {{cite book| last=Waddell | first=Joseph A. | author-link =  | year=1902 | title=Annals of Augusta County, Virginia, from 1726 to 1871: Supplement| publisher= C. R. Caldwell | location = [[Staunton, Virginia]] | isbn= | oclc = 3880311| url=https://archive.org/details/annalsofaugusta00wadd/mode/2up | accessdate=|ref=Waddell2 }}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mathews, Sampson}}\n[[Category:1737 births]]\n[[Category:1807 deaths]]\n[[Category:Virginia state senators]]\n[[Category:Virginia sheriffs]]\n[[Category:Virginia lawyers]]\n[[Category:Virginia militiamen in the American Revolution]]\n[[Category:People of Virginia in the French and Indian War]]\n[[Category:University and college founders]]\n[[Category:Washington and Lee University people]]\n[[Category:People from Augusta County, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Mathews family of Virginia and West Virginia]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name= Sampson Mathews\n|image= Sampson(2).jpg\n|caption=Silhouette of Sampson Mathews, 1756 <ref>{{cite book |last=Clem |first=Gladys |author-link= |date=1965 |title=It Happened Around Staunton in Virginia |url=https://books.google.com/?id=zYHhAAAAMAAJ |location=Augusta County, Virginia |publisher=McClure Print Company |page=21\u201323 |isbn=|oclc=3512763}}</ref>\n|alt=\n|order=\n|office= [[Virginia State Senate|Virginia State Senator]] from Augusta, Rockingham, Rockbridge, Shenandoah, and Pendleton counties\n|term= 1776\u20131780, 1790\n|predecessor =\n|successor = \n|lieutenant= \n|birth_date= c. 1737\n|birth_place= [[Augusta County, Virginia|Augusta County]],[[Colony of Virginia|Virginia]], [[British America]]\n|death_date= January 20, 1807 (aged 70)\n|death_place= [[Staunton, Virginia]], U.S.\n|spouse= Mary Lockhart<br>Mary Warwick\n|children= John<br>Sampson II<br>Two daughters<br>Martha (guardian ''ad litem'')\n|parents=[[John Mathews (American pioneer)|John Mathews]]<br>Ann Mathews\n|party= \n|religion= Presbyterian<ref>[[#Grigsby|Grigsby]], p. 88</ref>\n|relatives = [[Mathews family]]\n|profession    = merchant, soldier, politician\n|signature=Sampson Mathews signature, library of congress.png\n|signature_alt=\n|office2=\n|term_start2=\n|term_end2=\n|order3 =\n|term3 =\n|rank= [[File:US-O5 insignia.svg|30px]] [[Lieutenant colonel (United States)|Lieutenant Colonel]] of Virginia militia\n|allegiance= {{flagicon|Kingdom of Great Britain}} [[Kingdom of Great Britain|Great Britain]]<br>{{flagicon|United States of America|1777}} [[United States]]\n|branch= [[Virginia militia|Virginia provincial militia]]<br>Virginia militia\n|serviceyears= 1755-1774 (colonial forces)<br>1778-1783 (U.S. forces)\n|unit= \n|battles =French and Indian War<br>{{*}}[[Braddock expedition]]<br>Dunmore's War<br>{{*}}[[Battle of Point Pleasant]]<br>American Revolutionary War<br>{{*}}[[Raid of Richmond]]<br>{{*}}[[Battle of Green Spring]]<br>{{*}}[[Siege of Yorktown]]\n|awards=\n}}\n\n'''Sampson Mathews''' (c. 1737 \u2013 January 20, 1807) was an [[United States|American]] merchant, soldier, and legislator in the colony (and later U.S. state) of [[Virginia]].\n\nA son of John and Ann (Archer) Mathews, Mathews was an early merchant in the [[Shenandoah Valley]] region, where he and his brother [[George Mathews (Georgia)|George Mathews]] ran a series of mercantile outposts that extended to Atlantic trade networks. As war came to the colonies, Mathews took part in the [[Indian Wars]] and colonial revolutionary efforts. He was a member of the Augusta County [[Committee of Safety (American Revolution)|Committee of Safety]] that drafted the [[Augusta Resolves]], a precursor to the [[United States Declaration of Independence|Declaration of Independence]], and the [[Augusta Declaration]], a precursor to the [[Model Treaty]] (foreign policy), and the [[Articles of Confederation]] (the first U.S. constitution). \n\nMathews was elected to the inaugural [[Virginia State Senate]] in 1776. During the [[American Revolution]], he toured the [[American frontier|western frontier]] to fortify the colonial border from Indian attacks, and oversaw sail manufacture for the [[Continental Navy]]'s Virginia fleet. When turncoat [[Benedict Arnold]] enacted a surprise [[raid of Richmond]] in January 1781, Mathews lead Virginia militia forces in defense.\n\nMathews was an original [[trustee]] of Liberty Hall (later [[Washington and Lee University]]), when it was made into a college in 1776. This is the nation's ninth oldest institution of higher education. Mathews was a member of the [[Mathews family|Mathews political family]], which saw numerous members take part in state and national affairs over successive generations.\n\n\n== Early life and Indian Wars==\n{{See also|Mathews family}}\nSampson Mathews was born c. 1737 in [[Augusta County, Virginia]] to Ann (Archer) and [[John Mathews (American pioneer)|John Mathews]]. His parents were among the first settlers of Augusta County, likely having immigrated to America during the [[Scotch-Irish American|Scotch-Irish]] immigration of 1710\u20131775.<ref>[[#Waddell|Waddell]], p. 1</ref> His father was a notable member of the early Augusta County community, serving as a militia captain and public officer.<ref>[[#Peyton|Peyton]], p. 97</ref><ref>[[#Waddell|Waddell]], p. 137</ref> Sampson Mathews was educated at the Augusta Academy, a classical school founded in 1749.<ref>[[#Grigsby|Grigsby]], p. 88</ref> In his adolescence he worked in various crews to build roads in the county.<ref>[[#Chalkley|Chalkley]], p. 61\u201362</ref>\n\nOn the outbreak of the [[French and Indian War]] in 1755, Mathews was elected captain in the Augusta County militia,<ref>[[#Chalkley|Chalkley]], p. 183</ref> and accompanied [[George Washington]] under British General [[Edward Braddock]] on his ill-fated [[Braddock expedition]]. Up to four of Mathews' siblings, as well as his father, also took part in the expedition.<ref>[[#Henning|Henning]], p. 195</ref> Braddock's expedition met with the French and Indians in a [[meeting engagement]], from which the French and Indians gained the advantage. After suffering devastating casualties, the British retreated in disarray.<ref>{{cite book |last=Boreman |first=Walter R. |author-link= |date=2007 |title=The French and Indian War |url= |location=New York |publisher=Rutgers |page=55 |isbn=978-0-06-076185-1}}</ref> \n\nOn returning home, Mathews was elected [[sheriff]] of Augusta County in 1756, and also assumed the functions of [[chancellor]] of the county.<ref>[[#Waddell|Waddell]], p. 77</ref> For a time he worked as a reader for the local church, though this was apparently suspended due to a thinning of the population following the French and Indian War.<ref>[[#Waddell|Waddell]], p. 147</ref> Mathews married Mary Lockhart in 1759,<ref>[[#Morton|Morton]], p. 163</ref> with whom he had four children: John, Sampson, and two daughters who went on to be Mrs. Samuel Clark and Mrs. Alexander Nelson.<ref>[[#Waddell|Waddell]], p. 310</ref> By 1762, Mathews and his brother [[George Mathews (Georgia)|George Mathews]] had gone into a mercantile business in [[Staunton, Virginia]]. Quick success lead them to open numerous other stores and outposts in the Upper Valley, and to accumulate thousands of acres of land in the region.<ref>[[#Morton|Morton]], p. 162</ref> In their outposts they sold basic supplies but also specialty items including \"spelling books, silk, hats, \u201cozgn\u201d, handkerchiefs, silver, and even a tailor-made suit,\" and acted as unofficial bankers.<ref>{{cite journal |last1= Handley|first1=Harry |date=1963 |title=The Mathews Trading Post |url= http://gillilandtrails.org/documents/bios/bio_MathewsTradingPost.pdf|journal=The Journal of the Greenbrier Historical Society |volume= 1|issue=1 |pages= |doi= |access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref> Their enterprise grew to involve an extensive Atlantic trade network.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.georgiaencyclopedia.org/articles/government-politics/george-mathews-1739-1812 |title=George Mathews (1739\u20131812) |last=Ebel |first= Carol|date=2003 |website=New Georgia Encyclopedia |publisher=Georgia Humanities and the University of Georgia Press |access-date=April 16, 2020 |quote=}}</ref> The brothers imported and sold [[penal transportation|convict servants]] from Britain,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.vcdh.virginia.edu/gos/countyRecords/relatedAd.php?adFile=sg73.xml&adId=v1773111875 |title=Virginia Gazette, Williamsburg, November 11, 1773. |last= |first= |date= |website=The Geography of Slavery in Virginia |publisher=University of Virginia |access-date=April 16, 2020 |quote=}}</ref> and a small number of African slaves.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Herndon|first1=G. Melvin|title=George Mathews, Frontier Patriot|journal=Virginia Magazine of History and Biography|date=1969|volume=77|issue=3|page=310|jstor=4247487}}</ref> In total, their dealings accounted for a \"great share\" of the trade in the region.<ref>{{cite book| last1=Van Schreeven| first1= William| last2=Scribner| first2= Robert| last3=Tarter| first3= Brent| author-link =  | year=1973| title=Revolutionary Virginia, the road to independence, vol. 5. Independence and the Fifth convention| publisher= University Press of Virginia | location = [[Charlottesville, Virginia]] | isbn= | oclc = 802770| url= |accessdate=|ref=Van Schreeven et al.}}</ref>\n\nMathews was appointed a [[justice of the peace]] for Augusta County in 1764, and in that role he presided over [[misdemeanors]] and other civil cases in the county.<ref>[[#Waddell2|Waddell2]], p. 439</ref> He also served as a member of the [[Vestryman|vestry]] for Augusta Parish around this time,<ref>[[#Waddell|Waddell]], p. 167</ref> with the vestry being the ''[[de facto]]'' local government for the county.<ref>[[#Peyton|Peyton]], p. 97</ref> Mathews was granted a [[liquor license]] in 1765,<ref>[[#Chalkley|Chalkley]], p. 122</ref> and his tavern and inn in Staunton, a \"long frame building, a story and a half high, with [[dormer]] windows,\"<ref>[[#Waddell|Waddell]], p. 166</ref> soon became the most fashionable of its kind in Staunton.<ref>[[#Morton|Morton]], p. 163</ref> In 1768, Mathews became the guardian ''ad litem'' for a niece, Martha Mathews, on the premature death of her father, Joshua Mathews. <ref>[[#Chalkley|Chalkley]], p. 149</ref> She would later marry [[Thomas Posey]], whose father had been a guest at Mathews' inn and probably arranged their meeting.<ref name=Posey>Posey, John Thornton.  ''General Thomas Posey: Son of the American Revolution.'' East Lansing, MI: Michigan State University Press, 1992. Pages 17\u201318 {{ISBN|0-87013-316-0}}</ref> \n\nIn 1773, Mathews and others solicited subscriptions for a new academy in the Valley. This academy, named Liberty Hall and located in [[Lexington, Virginia]], was officially incorporated by the Commonwealth of Virginia in 1782, with Mathews serving as an original trustee.<ref>[[#Grigsby|Grigsby]], p. 87</ref> Liberty Hall was eventually renamed [[Washington and Lee University]],<ref>[[#Waddell|Waddell]], p. 303</ref> and is the nation's ninth oldest institution of higher education.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://my.wlu.edu/about-wandl/history-and-traditions/a-brief-history |title=A Brief History |last= |first= |date= |website=Washington & Lee University |publisher=Washington & Lee University |access-date=April 16, 2020 |quote=}}</ref>\n\nIn fall of 1774, [[List of colonial governors of Virginia|Royal Governor]] [[Lord Dunmore]] assembled a 1000-man invasion of Indian territory, culling recruits from Augusta County. Mathews' tavern served as headquarters for the local militia during preparations. A possibly [[apocryphal]] story arose that the men of George Mathews' regiment marked their height on a wall of Sampson Mathews' tavern, revealing that all but two men were over six feet tall.<ref>[[#Waddell|Waddell]], p. 220\u2013221</ref> For the expedition, Mathews served as [[chief procurement officer]] for General [[Andrew Lewis (soldier)|Andrew Lewis]], and oversaw the driving of 500 pack horses, 54,000 pounds of flour, and 108 cattle for the march from Augusta to [[Point Pleasant, West Virginia|Point Pleasant]], for which the troops gave him the nickname \"Master Driver of Cattle.\"<ref>[[#Waddell|Waddell]], p. 220</ref> An early Ohio historian said of Mathews' march:\n{{Quote\n|His route lay wholly through a trackless forest. All his baggage, his provisions, and even his ammunition, had to be transported on pack-horses, that were clambering about among tall cliffs, or winding their way among dangerous defiles, ascending or descending the lofty summits of the Alleghenies. . . During nineteen entire days, this gallant band pressed forward descending from the height of the Allegheny mountains to the mouth of the Kenawha [sic], a distance of one hundred and sixty miles.<ref>{{cite book |last=Lewis |first=Virgil |author-link= |date=1909 |title=History of the Battle of Point Pleasant Fought Between White Men and Indians at the Mouth of the Great Kanawha River (now Point Pleasant, West Virginia) Monday, October 10th, 1774 |url= |location=Charleston, West Virginia |publisher=Tribune Printing Company |page=31 |isbn=1888265590}}</ref>}}\n\nOctober 10, 1774,  The [[Battle of Point Pleasant]] was fought between the Virginia militia and Indians from the [[Shawnee]] and [[Mingo]] tribes along the [[Ohio River]]. Various sources credit either [[Colonel (United Kingdom)|Colonel]] [[Andrew Lewis (soldier)|Andrew Lewis]] or [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|Captain]] George Mathews with a flanking maneuver that initiated [[Shawnee]] Chief [[Cornstalk]]'s retreat and secured victory for the colonial militia.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Herndon|first1=G. Melvin|title=George Mathews, Frontier Patriot|journal=Virginia Magazine of History and Biography|date=1969|volume=77|issue=3|page=312|jstor=4247487}}</ref>\n\n== American Revolution ==\nThe months following the Dunmore's War saw tension rise between the British and the colonies. The [[Virginia House of Burgesses]] began to resist the Crown, and in retaliation Lord Dunmore dissolved it in May 1774. This lead the Burgesses to form the extralegal [[Virginia Conventions]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.encyclopediavirginia.org/House_of_Burgesses#start_entry|title= House of Burgesses |last=Gottlieb|first=Matthew S. |publisher=Virginia Foundation of the Humanities|accessdate=April 16, 2020|ref=gottlieb}}</ref>\n\n===Revolutionary activities===\nOn February 22, 1775, Mathews took part in the first documented revolutionary meeting in Augusta County, as a member of the county's [[Committee of Safety (American Revolution)|Committee of Safety]].<ref>[[#Waddell|Waddell]], p. 235</ref> These county committees were an outgrowth of the Virginia [[Committee of Correspondence]], the state's patriotic shadow government. The Augusta County committee met in Staunton, Virginia, and drafted the [[Augusta Resolves]] to assert their county's commitment to \"enjoy the free exercise of conscience, and of human nature.\" The committee then elected delegates to the [[Second Virginia Convention]] in March 1775, with Mathews among those who drafted instructions for the delegates.<ref>[[#Waddell|Waddell]], p. 235</ref> The Augusta Resolves were endorsed in a meeting of [[freehold (law)|freeholders]] of Augusta County and published in Pinkney's March 16, 1775 [[Virginia Gazette]]. Historian Jim Glanville states that the resolutions of Virginia's four western counties (Augusta, Botetourt, [[Fincastle Resolutions|Fincastle]], and Pittsylvania) are best viewed as a whole and were \"by far the most significant statements in favor of American liberty\" of the county resolutions that were a direct precursor to the [[Declaration of Independence]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1= Glanville|first1=Jim |date=2010 |title=The Fincastle Resolutions |url=https://vtechworks.lib.vt.edu/bitstream/handle/10919/88172/SR_v14_glanville.pdf?sequence=1&isAllowed=y |journal=The Smithfield Review |volume=XIV |issue= |pages=78 |doi= |access-date=April 16, 2020 }}</ref>\n\nMathews, with two other representatives of the Augusta County committee, met with members of the counties of [[Albemarle County, Virginia|Albemarle]], [[Amherst County, Virginia|Amherst]], and [[Buckingham County, Virginia|Buckingham]] in September 1775 to organize militia units in reparation for war against Britain. Augusta County resolved to raise four companies of fifty men each, with the other counties raising two companies of fifty men each. George Mathews was given command of the ten companies.<ref>[[#Waddell|Waddell]], p. 245</ref>\n{{quote box\n |quote  = \"It [the Augusta Declaration] is the first deliberate expression of the policy of establishing an independent state government and a permanent confederation of the States which our parliamentary journals contain. . .This memorial from Augusta . . .deserves to be stereotyped as the Magna Charta of the West.\"<ref>[[#Grigsby|Grigsby 1890(2)]], p. 66</ref>\n |source = - [[Hugh Blair Grigsby]], ''Washington and Lee University Historical Papers, Volumes 1\u20132 (1890)''\n |width  = 35%\n |align  = right\n}}\nBy the time of the [[Fifth Virginia Convention]] in May 1776, many its delegates knew the issue of independence would be addressed, and some came with prepared statements on the subject.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Dunaway, Jr. |first1=W.F. |date=1904 |title= The Virginia Conventions of the Revolution |journal=Virginia Law Register |volume=10 |issue=7 |pages=581 |doi= 10.2307/1100650|jstor=1100650 }}</ref> However, over the first several sessions, the Convention dealt with matters largely related to the ongoing war effort.<ref>{{cite book| last1=Van Schreeven| first1= William| last2=Scribner| first2= Robert| last3=Tarter| first3= Brent| author-link =  | year=1973| title=Revolutionary Virginia, the road to independence, vol. 7. Independence and the Fifth convention| publisher= University Press of Virginia | location = [[Charlottesville, Virginia]] | isbn= | oclc = 802770| url= | accessdate=|page= p. 124, n. 3|ref=Van Schreeven et al.}}</ref> On May 10, 1776, [[Thomas Lewis (Virginia)|Thomas Lewis]] broached the independence issue when, on behalf of the Augusta County Committee of Safety, he introduced the [[Augusta Declaration]] to the Convention. This was the first official proposal for the creation of a permanent and independent union of states and national government from any of the Thirteen Colonies. Virginia history scholar [[Hugh Blair Grigsby]] states the Augusta Declaration \"deserves to be stereotyped as the [[Magna Charta]] of the West\" for its precedent in calling for this governmental mode, which was adopted in the creation of the United States of America.<ref>[[#Grigsby|Grigsby]], p. 66</ref> The  proposals for independence, a confederation of colonies, and a national government were passed by the Virginia Convention on March 15 and forwarded to the [[Second Continental Congress]],<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/patrickhenrylif00henrgoog/page/n14|title=Patrick Henry; Life, Correspondence and Speeches|first=William Wirt|last=Henry|authorlink=William Wirt Henry|page=401|publisher=Charles Scribner's Sons|location= [[New York, New York]]|year=1891| oclc = 727087|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref> which then initiated the drafting of the Declaration of Independence, the [[Articles of Confederation]], and the [[Model Treaty]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://history.state.gov/milestones/1776-1783/model-treaty |title=The Model Treaty, 1776 |last= |first= |date= |website= United States Office of the Historian |publisher= United States Dept. of State|access-date=April 19, 2020 |quote=}}</ref>\n\n===Virginia State Senate and war efforts===\n\nMathews was elected to the [[Virginia State Senate]], the successor to the [[Virginia Governor's Council]], for its inaugural session of 1776, representing Augusta and [[Shenandoah County, Virginia|Dunmore]] counties. He remained a member of the state senate through 1780, representing Augusta, [[Rockingham County, Virginia|Rockingham]], [[Rockbridge County, Virginia|Rockbridge]], and [[Shenandoah County, Virginia|Shenandoah]] counties from 1778\u20131780.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://vavh.electionstats.com/php/bio.php?pid=4813 |title=The Virginia Elections and State Elected Officials Database Project, 1776-2007 |last=Kromkowski |first= C. |date=2005 |website=The Virginia Elections and State Elected Officials Database Project, 1776\u20132007 |publisher=University of Virginia Library |access-date=April 16, 2020 |quote=|ref=Kromkowski}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote box\n |quote  = Of the public rope-walks, manufactories of ducking, sail-cloth, etc, the most important was that at Warwick on the James, five miles south of Richmond. Skilled sail-makers were probably drawn from the Ulster settlement in the Valley of Virginia, some of whose members had doubtless served an apprenticeship in Ireland. The assignment of Col. Sampson Mathews, of August County, to a committee on the supervision of naval equipment is not without significance.<ref>{{cite book |last=Stewart |first=Robert A. |author-link= |date=1934 |title=The History of Virginia's Navy of the Revolution |url= |location=Charlottesville, Virginia |publisher=Mitchell & Hotchkiss |page=136 |isbn=\t9780806348711}}</ref>\n |source = --Robert Armistead Stewart, ''The History of Virginia's Navy of the Revolution'' (1934).\n |width  = 35%\n |align  = right\n}}\n\nDuring its inaugural session, the senate sought to promote the [[Continental Navy]]'s Virginia fleet. At this time, Virginia had more land and manufactories devoted to naval purposes than any of the colonies, but it faced a distinct lack of materials needed to create linen sail cloth. Mathews, along with Alexander St. Clair, was therefore appointed to erect and superintend a factory in Staunton, Virginia for the making of sail material from flax grown by Augusta County farmers.<ref>[[#Waddell|Waddell]], p. 251</ref>\n\nHowever, other matters soon drew Mathews elsewhere. In the fall of 1777, Shawnee Chief Cornstalk made a diplomatic visit to the American [[Fort Randolph (West Virginia)|Fort Randolph]], on the site present-day [[Point Pleasant, West Virginia]]. Virginia militiamen took Cornstalk hostage at the fort, and on November 10, 1777, killed him without cause.<ref>[[#Tillson|Tillson]], p. 141\u2013142</ref> This lead to an immediate backlash from the Shawnee. Congress, sensing the urgency of the situation, passed a resolution on November 20 to send commissioners out west with the aim of restoring friendly relations between the Shawnee and the colonists that had been years in the making. Mathews was appointed to represent Virginia, and [[George Clymer]] for Pennsylvania. The men arrived at [[Fort Pitt (Pennsylvania)|Fort Pitt]] in mid-March, and reported back to Congress in late-April that the British in Detroit were aiding the Shawnee and nearby Delaware tribes in their attacks. Further, they believed the colonists may well be able to restore friendly relations with the Indians by capturing [[Fort Detroit]] from the British, and thus weakening the Indians' position.<ref>{{cite journal |last1= Bushnell|first1=David |date=1924 |title= The Proposed Expedition against Detroit, 1778|journal=The Virginia Magazine of History and Biography |volume=32 |issue=1 |pages=66 |doi= |jstor=4243948 |ref=Bushnell}}</ref> They proposed a force of 3,000 be dedicated to this cause.<ref>{{cite book |last=Pieper |first=Thomas |author-link= |date=1980 |title=Fort Laurens, 1778-1779: The Revolutionary War in Ohio |url=https://books.google.com/?id=9aoJVOjymwIC&dq=%22sampson+matthews%22 |location= |publisher=Kent State University Press |page=13 |isbn=9780873382403}}</ref> Congress, however, deferred the recommendation, considering it too costly, and instead sent troops to fortify their western borders.<ref>[[#Bushnell|Bushnell]]</ref>\n\n===Military service===\n{{Main article|Raid of Richmond}}\n[[File:Benedict Arnold. Copy of engraving by H. B. Hall after John Trumbull, published 1879., 1931 - 1932 - NARA - 532921.tif|thumb|upright=1.0|left|British Brigadier General [[Benedict Arnold]] invaded Virginia by surprise in 1781.]]\nMathews was appointed [[Lieutenant colonel (United States)|lieutenant colonel]] of Augusta County militia in May 1778,<ref>[[#Chalkley|Chalkley]], p. 197</ref> giving him command of the county militia and a field commission of [[Colonel (United States)|colonel]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |title=Virginia's Soldiers in the Revolution (Continued) |journal=The Virginia Magazine of History and Biography |year= 1914|volume=22 |issue=1 |pages=57-67 (58) |doi= |jstor= 4243322}}</ref> This was a position normally given to the most prominent leader of the county.<ref>[[#Tillson|Tillson]], p. 47</ref> Mathews called out the militia for a three month tour in April 1779, on account of Indian threats in [[Tygart Valley River|Tygart Valley, Virginia]].<ref>[[#McCallister|McCallister]], p. 105</ref> The expedition resulted in several scouting missions, but no battle. <ref>[[#Waddell|Waddell]], p. 258</ref> In October 1780, Mathews requested to disqualify himself form serving the rest of his term in the Virginia State Senate.<ref>[[#Chalkley|Chalkley]], p. 217</ref>\n\nOn January 1, 1781, British [[Brigadier (United Kingdom)|Brigadier General]] [[Benedict Arnold]] launched a surprise invasion of Virginia. For five days he sailed up the [[James River]] to virtually no resistance. Virginia Governor [[Thomas Jefferson]] fled the capitol of [[Richmond, Virginia|Richmond]] as Arnold approached, and Arnold thereafter burned and looted the city. Jefferson called out militia commanders throughout the state to help to repel Arnold's invasion. He directed Mathews to march to [[Fredericksburg, Virginia|Fredericksburg]],<ref>[[#Waddell|Waddell]], p. 278\u2013279</ref> and report to [[Brigadier general (United States)|Brigadier General]] [[George Weedon]]. Mathews wrote to the governor the next day, confirming that he and a company of 250 would head to Fredericksburg in the morning. Mathews also recruited his son-in-law [[Major (United States)|Major]] Thomas Posey to join him with his troops for the march.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://founders.archives.gov/documents/Jefferson/01-04-02-0432 |title=To Thomas Jefferson from Sampson Mathews, 13 January 1781 |last= |first= |date= |website=Founders Online |publisher=National Archives |access-date=2020-04-10 |quote=I have Prevailed with Major Posey to go with me who will be of great Service.}}</ref><ref>[[#Waddell|Waddell]], p. 279, p. 310</ref>\n\nMathews made the approximately 100 mile march from Staunton to Fredericksburg in four days. After spending an additional four days in Fredericksburg, Mathews was directed by [[Major General (United States)|Major General]] [[Peter Muhlenberg]] to turn to [[Bowling Green, Virginia|Bowling Green]] about 30 miles south. There Mathews wrote to Jefferson urging that he make materials available \"for the repair of the arms of the militia.\"\n<ref>{{cite web |url=https://founders.archives.gov/documents/Jefferson/01-04-02-0523 |title=From Sampson Mathews, with Jefferson's Instructions to George Muter, 21 January 1781 |last= |first= |date= |website=Founders Online |publisher=National Archives |access-date=April 16, 2020 |quote=The Bearer Mr. Chas. Cocke will wait on your Excellency For an order For these articles which are very much wanting.}}</ref> Muhlenberg then directed Mathews to [[Cabin Point, Virginia|Cabin Point]] in [[Smithfield, Virginia]], some 80 miles southeast to the mouth of the James. Mathews wrote to Jefferson on the 29th that his march had been delayed at the James River for several days due to poor weather and insufficiency of the transport boats. He described the lack of basic provisions in his camp, including tents and ammunition, and the poor health of many from exposure to the winter elements, which lead him to fear mutiny.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://founders.archives.gov/documents/Jefferson/01-04-02-0574 |title=To Thomas Jefferson from Sampson Mathews, 29 January 1781 |last= |first= |date= |website=Founders Online |publisher=National Archives |access-date=April 16, 2020 |quote=Is afraid the men will mutiny because the \u201cmarch is So Severe\u201d and the \u201cduty on the Lines will add To the fatigue.\u201d}}</ref><ref>[[#Waddell|Waddell]], p. 279</ref>\n\nJefferson responded on the 31st, relaying that there were some 150 tents \"somewhere,\" and that he would attempt locate and direct them toward Mathews, acknowledging that Mathews' position \"nearest the enemy's lines\" validated the expediency of these supplies.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://founders.archives.gov/documents/Jefferson/01-04-02-0594 |title=From Thomas Jefferson to Sampson Mathews and John Bowyer, 31 January 1781 |last= |first= |date= |website=Founders Online |publisher=National Archives |access-date=April 16, 2020 |quote= I have given orders to find in whose possession they are, and as soon as it is known I will inform Baron Steuben and communicate to him your want,...}}</ref> By the 15th of February, the Virginia militia had bottled up Arnold's forces in [[Portsmouth, Virginia]], with Mathews commanding the advanced post alongside 350 riflemen.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://founders.archives.gov/documents/Jefferson/01-04-02-0776 |title=To Thomas Jefferson from Robert Lawson, 15 February 1781 |last= |first= |date= |website=Founders Online |publisher=National Archives |access-date=April 16, 2020 |quote=}}</ref><ref>[[#Waddell|Waddell]], p. 279\u2013280</ref> Nothing else is known of the Mathews' regiment during this expedition, and the Augusta County militia returned home in mid-April.<ref>[[#Waddell|Waddell]], p. 279</ref> \n\nThe Virginia General Assembly, having fled Arnold's force in Richmond, met in the [[Trinity Episcopal Church (Staunton, Virginia)|Trinity Episcopal Church]] in Staunton, Virginia from June 7 to 23. On June 12, the Assembly voted to elect [[Thomas Nelson Jr.]] as the [[List of governors of Virginia|4th governor of Virginia]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.encyclopediavirginia.org/The_Election_of_Thomas_Nelson_as_Governor_June_12_1781 |title=The Election of Governor Thomas Nelson |last= |first= |date= |website=Encyclopedia Virginia |publisher=Virginia Humanities |access-date=April 18, 2020 |quote=}}</ref> Mathews, who remained a justice of the peace for Augusta County, administered the [[oath of office]] to Nelson the following week, on June 19.<ref>[[#Chalkley|Chalkley]], p. 527</ref> Mathews quickly left again for eastern Virginia, bringing a regiment to [[James City, Virginia]] where it saw action in the [[Battle of Green Spring]].<ref>[[#Morton|Morton]], p. 95\u201396</ref> Mathews' field lieutenant colonel, William Boyer, was captured during the battle.<ref>[[#McCallister|McCallister], p. 64</ref>. On August 8,  Mathews went to [[Yorktown, Virginia]], where the [[Siege of Yorktown]] proved to be the last major battle of the war.<ref>[[#Waddell2|Waddell2]], p. 491</ref> By November 1781 Mathews had returned from battle and resumed his duties in the Virginia State Senate, being appointed to the Privy Council on November 30.<ref>{{cite book |last=Virginia General Assembly |author-link= |date=1828 |title=1781 Journal of the Virginia House of Delegates |url=https://archive.org/details/journalofhouseof178186virg/page/n57/mode/2up |location=Richmond, Virginia |publisher=Commonwealth of Virginia |page=23 |isbn=}}</ref> Mathews stepped down as lieutenant colonel of Augusta County militia on November 18, 1783.<ref>[[#Chalkley|Chalkley]], p. 233</ref>\n\n==Later life==\nMathews served a final term in the Virginia State Senate in 1790, representing Augusta, Rockingham, Rockbridge, Shenandoah, and [[Pendleton County, West Virginia|Pendleton]] counties.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://vavh.electionstats.com/php/bio.php?pid=4813 |title=The Virginia Elections and State Elected Officials Database Project, 1776-2007 |last=Kromkowski |first= C. |date=2005 |website=The Virginia Elections and State Elected Officials Database Project, 1776\u20132007 |publisher=University of Virginia Library |access-date=April 16, 2020 |quote=|ref=Kromkowski}}</ref> He then served as a justice of the peace and the first [[High Sheriff|high sheriff]] of [[Bath County, Virginia|Bath County]] when it was formed from Augusta County in 1791.<ref>[[#Morton|Morton]], p. 136</ref><ref>[[#Waddell2|Waddell2]], p. 481</ref> He also served as an original trustee for [[Hot Springs, Virginia]] on its formation in 1793.<ref>[[#Morton|Morton]], p. 47</ref> He lived in Bath County about ten years at his estate, Cloverdale.<ref>[[#Waddell|Waddell]], p. 344</ref> On the death of his wife Mary, he married again to a Mary Warwick.<ref>[[#Morton|Morton]], p. 163</ref> He resided in Staunton, Virginia in later life, in a log house at the intersection of Beverly and Water Streets. He died in Staunton in 1807.<ref>[[#Waddell|Waddell]], p. 310</ref>\n\nMathews' son, Sampson Mathews II, served as a Virginia Delegate from [[Bath County, Virginia|Bath County]] for the 1809\u20131810 session of the Virginia General Assembly, representing the [[Federalist party]].<ref>[[#Grigsby|Grigsby]], p. 88</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://vavh.electionstats.com/php/bio.php?pid=4805 |title=The Virginia Elections and State Elected Officials Database Project, 1776-2007 |last=Kromkowski |first= C. |date=2005 |website=The Virginia Elections and State Elected Officials Database Project, 1776-2007 |publisher=University of Virginia Library |access-date=April 16, 2020 |quote=|ref=}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book| last=Chalkley | first=Lyman| author-link =  | year=1912 | title=Chronicles of the Scotch-Irish Settlement in Virginia | publisher= The Commonwealth printing co | location = [[Rosslyn, Virginia]] |  isbn= | oclc = 2575649 | url= https://archive.org/details/chroniclesscotc00lockgoog/page/n6 | accessdate= |ref=Chalkley }}\n* {{cite book| last=Grigsby | first= Hugh Blair| author-link =Hugh Blair Grigsby  | year=1890 | title=Washington and Lee University Historical Papers, Volumes 1\u20132 | publisher= The New York Public Library |page=88 |location = [[Lexington, Virginia]] |  isbn= | oclc = | url= https://books.google.com/?id=9p4gAAAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage | accessdate=|ref=Grigsby}}\n* {{cite book| last=Henning | first=William W.| author-link =  | year=1809 | title=The Statutes at Large: Being a Collection of all the Laws of Virginia, vol. 7| publisher= R. & W. & G. Bartow | location = New York City |  isbn= | oclc = 426084215 | url= https://archive.org/details/statutesatlargeb07virg| accessdate= |ref=Henning }}\n* {{cite book |last=McCallister |first=J.T. |author-link= |date=1913 |title=Virginia militia in the Revolutionary War : McAllister's data |url=https://archive.org/details/militiaintherevolu00mcalrich/mode/2up |location=Hot Springs, Virginia |publisher=McCallister Publishing Co. |page= |isbn=|oclc=1536303|ref=McCallister}}\n* {{cite book| last=Morton | first=Oren| author-link = | year=1978| title= Annals of Bath County, Virginia | publisher= C.J. Carrier Co.| location = [[Harrisonburg, Virginia]] |  isbn= | oclc = 656749557 | url= https://archive.org/details/annalsofbathcoun00mort/ | accessdate=April 17, 2020 |ref=Morton }}\n* {{cite book| last=Peyton | first=John L. | author-link =  | year=1882 | title=History of Augusta County, Virginia| publisher= Samuel M. Yost & son | location = Unknown |  isbn= 1230356312 | oclc = 923774044 | url= https://archive.org/details/historyaugustac00peytgoog| accessdate= |ref=Peyton }}\n* {{cite book |last=Tillson, Jr. |first=Albert |author-link= |date=1991 |title=Gentry and Common Folk: Political Culture on a Virginia Frontier 1740\u20131789 |url=https://uknowledge.uky.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1084&context=upk_united_states_history |location=Lexington, KY |publisher=The University Press of Kentucky |page= |isbn=9780813155173}}\n* {{cite book| last=Waddell | first=Joseph A. | author-link =  | year=1902 | title=Annals of Augusta County, Virginia, from 1726 to 1871 | publisher= C. R. Caldwell | location = [[Staunton, Virginia]] | isbn= | oclc = 3880311| url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_rZbEC1kEdpcC | accessdate=|ref=Waddell }}\n* {{cite book| last=Waddell | first=Joseph A. | author-link =  | year=1902 | title=Annals of Augusta County, Virginia, from 1726 to 1871: Supplement| publisher= C. R. Caldwell | location = [[Staunton, Virginia]] | isbn= | oclc = 3880311| url=https://archive.org/details/annalsofaugusta00wadd/mode/2up | accessdate=|ref=Waddell2 }}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mathews, Sampson}}\n[[Category:1737 births]]\n[[Category:1807 deaths]]\n[[Category:Virginia state senators]]\n[[Category:Virginia sheriffs]]\n[[Category:Virginia lawyers]]\n[[Category:Virginia militiamen in the American Revolution]]\n[[Category:People of Virginia in the French and Indian War]]\n[[Category:University and college founders]]\n[[Category:Washington and Lee University people]]\n[[Category:People from Augusta County, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Mathews family of Virginia and West Virginia]]\n", "name_user": "Nick-D", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRevolutionary activities:typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sampson_Mathews"}
{"title_page": "Viburnum", "text_new": "{{Automatic taxobox\n|image = Viburnum opulus C.jpg\n|image_caption = ''[[Viburnum opulus]]'' fruit\n|taxon = Viburnum\n|authority = [[Carl Linnaeus|L.]]<ref name=\"grin\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ars-grin.gov/cgi-bin/npgs/html/genus.pl?12699 |title=Genus: ''Viburnum'' L. |work=Germplasm Resources Information Network |publisher=United States Department of Agriculture |date=2006-11-03 |accessdate=2010-11-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605092034/http://www.ars-grin.gov/cgi-bin/npgs/html/genus.pl?12699 |archive-date=2011-06-05 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|subdivision_ranks = Species\n|subdivision = See text\n}}\n\n'''''Viburnum'''''  is a [[genus]] of about 150\u2013175 [[species]] of [[flowering plant]]s in the moschatel [[family (botany)|family]] [[Adoxaceae]]. Its current classification is based on [[molecular phylogeny]].<ref name=\"winkworth\">{{Cite journal | doi = 10.3732/ajb.92.4.653 | title = Viburnum phylogeny based on combined molecular data: implications for taxonomy and biogeography | year = 2005 | author = Winkworth, R. C. | journal = American Journal of Botany | volume = 92 | pages = 653\u201366 | last2 = Donoghue | first2 = M. J. | issue = 4 | pmid = 21652443 | url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/c1d5550df918f83efcf115cd32b6f5eaf61f1f12 }}</ref> It was previously included in the honeysuckle family [[Caprifoliaceae]].<ref name=\"grin\"/>\n\nThe member species are evergreen or [[deciduous]] [[Shrub|shrubs]] or (in a few cases) small trees native throughout the temperate Northern Hemisphere, with a few species extending into tropical montane regions in South America and southeast Asia. In Africa, the genus is confined to the [[Atlas Mountains]].\n\n==Name==\nThe generic name originated in [[Latin]], where it referred to ''[[Viburnum lantana|V.&nbsp;lantana]]''.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zIOvJSJs-IkC |first=Umberto |last=Quattrocchi |title=CRC World Dictionary of Plant Names: Common Names, Scientific Names, Eponyms, Synonyms, and Etymology |volume=IV R-Z |year=2000 |publisher=Taylor & Francis US |isbn=978-0-8493-2678-3 |page=2793}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\nThe [[leaf|leaves]] are [[opposite leaves|opposite]], simple, and entire, toothed or lobed; cool temperate species are [[deciduous]], while most of the warm temperate species are [[evergreen]]. Some species are densely hairy on the shoots and leaves, with star-shaped hairs.\n\nThe [[flower]]s are produced in [[corymb]]s 5\u201315&nbsp;cm across, each flower white to cream or pink, small, 3\u20135&nbsp;mm across, with five petals, strongly fragrant in some species. The [[gynoecium]] has three connate [[carpel]]s with the [[nectary]] on top of the gynoecium. Some species also have a fringe of large, showy sterile flowers around the perimeter of the corymb to act as a pollinator target.\n\nThe [[fruit]] is a spherical, oval, or somewhat flattened [[drupe]], red to purple, blue, or black, and containing a single [[seed]]; some are edible for humans, but many others are mildly [[poison]]ous. The leaves are eaten by the [[larva]]e of [[list of Lepidoptera that feed on Viburnum|many Lepidoptera species]].\n\nBirds eat the berries of ''Viburnum obovatum'' (also called Walter Viburnum after [[Thomas Walter (botanist)|Thomas Walter]]).<ref>{{cite book|last=Little|first=Elbert L.|title=The Audubon Society Field Guide to North American Trees: Eastern Region|publisher=Knopf|location=New York|year=1980|isbn=0-394-50760-6|p=674}}</ref>\n\n==Species==\n{{clear}}\nAround 165 species are described. A 2014 phylogenetic study<ref name = clement201406chloroplasttreeViburnum/> proposed the following phylogenetic scheme and sections:\n\n{{cot | title = ''Viburnum'' Phylogenetic Tree | expand = yes}}\n{{clade|style=font-size:85%\n  |label1 = [[Viburnum]]|1 = {{clade\n    |1 = ''[[Viburnum clemensiae|V. clemensiae]]''\n    |label2 = Regulaviburnum|2 = {{clade\n      |label1 = Valvatotinus|1 = {{clad